ríticos entre setores\\\\n- Estratégia temporária: adapter layer ou freeze-clean-first\\\\n- Critério para considerar S2 “unificado” e S9 “desbloqueado”\\\\n\\\\n## Best items to hand Claude Code\\\\n\\\\n### Batch A — highest leverage first\\\\n- criar/actualizar schemas JSON dos artefactos core por setor\\\\n- implementar shared `scene_bible` I/O contract\\\\n- implementar shared checkpoint helpers\\\\n- implementar shared schema validation runtime\\\\n- definir enums/structures para structured errors\\\\n\\\\n### Batch B — minimal productive substrate\\\\n- PM: `read_pub`, `job_builder`, `job_validator`\\\\n- VO-lite: `video_dir_initializer`, `checkpoint_resolver`, `sector_dispatcher` mínimo\\\\n- wrappers: Sheets, TTS, WhisperX\\\\n\\\\n### Batch C — first implementable chain\\\\n- S1 validators: `screenplay_validator`, `polish_validator`, `scene_bible_schema_validator`\\\\n- S2 core: `tts_generator`, `audio_transcriber`, `timestamp_aligner`, `bible_updater`\\\\n- S4 core: `asset_json_schema_validator`, `asset_deduplicator`, `asset_license_validator`\\\\n\\\\n## Top traps to avoid during the session\\\\n- começar por S6 porque parece mais excitante\\\\n- discutir arquitectura nova sem congelar contratos existentes\\\\n- implementar VO cedo demais\\\\n- aceitar docs centrais e mirror como se ambos fossem verdade ao mesmo tempo\\\\n- codar sobre naming ambíguo (`b#_` / `s#_`, `scene_id` / `moment_id`, `duration_frames` / `duration_ms`)\\\\n- entrar em S9 antes de congelar S7/S8\\\\n- deixar `scene_bible` crescer sem governação forte\\\\n- sair da sessão com “direcção” mas sem decisões canónicas escritas\\\\n\\\\n## Suggested meeting / workflow cadence\\\\n- **0-10 min:** alinhar missão da sessão + definir o que precisa sair decidido\\\\n- **10-35 min:** freeze de naming, docs fonte de verdade, mirrors, handoffs\\\\n- **35-60 min:** fechar contracts core (`scene_bible`, checkpoints, errors)\\\\n- **60-85 min:** transformar decisões em tickets claros para Claude Code\\\\n- **85-100 min:** rever o que ficou fora, dependências e ordem exacta do próximo lote\\\\n\\\\n## Session close checklist\\\\n- [ ] naming canónico decidido\\\\n- [ ] docs centrais prioritários identificados para update\\\\n- [ ] política de mirror decidida\\\\n- [ ] `scene_bible` contract fechado\\\\n- [ ] checkpoint contract fechado\\\\n- [ ] batch P0 para Claude Code definido\\\\n- [ ] explicitamente adiado: VO pleno + S9 pesado + S6 browser-heavy\\\\n\\\\n## Default recommendation if debate stalls\\\\n- **Follow this order:**\\\\n  - Freeze\\\\n  - Shared infra\\\\n  - PM core\\\\n  - S1\\\\n  - S2 unificado\\\\n  - S4\\\\n  - S3 hardening\\\\n  - S5\\\\n  - S6\\\\n  - S7\\\\n  - S8\\\\n  - S9\\\\n  - S10\\\\n  - VO pleno\\\\n\\\"}\"\n            }\n          ],\n          \"api\": \"openai-codex-responses\",\n          \"provider\": \"openai-codex\",\n          \"model\": \"gpt-5.4\",\n          \"usage\": {\n            \"input\": 10768,\n            \"output\": 1531,\n            \"totalTokens\": 22795,\n            \"cacheRead\": 10496,\n            \"cacheWrite\": 0,\n            \"cost\": {\n              \"total\": 0.052509\n            }\n          },\n          \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\",\n          \"timestamp\": 1774794498630,\n          \"responseId\": \"resp_0720d1a20670abea0169c937045bd08191ba9025931419b0a6\",\n          \"__openclaw\": {\n            \"id\": \"c4c10c65\",\n            \"seq\": 8\n          }\n        },\n        {\n          \"role\": \"assistant\",\n          \"content\": [\n            {\n              \"type\": \"text\",\n              \"text\": \"Concluído.\\n\\nCriei o ficheiro:\\n- `C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\reviews\\\\tobias_review_29mar\\\\22_session_battle_board.md`\\n\\nO board está comprimido e operacional, cobrindo:\\n- ordem recomendada para a sessão ao vivo\\n- status por setor: ready / blocked / do later\\n- decisões principais a fechar live\\n- batches prontos para entregar ao Claude Code\\n- traps a evitar\\n- cadence sugerida da reunião/workflow\\n- checklist de fecho\\n\\nPonto central do board:\\n- a sessão deve optimizar para **freeze de contratos + shared infra + lote P0 implementável**\\n- e **evitar cair em VO pleno / S9 / S6 browser-heavy cedo demais**.\",\n              \"textSignature\": \"{\\\"v\\\":1,\\\"id\\\":\\\"msg_0720d1a20670abea0169c937380eac819181ebf262c7eff349\\\",\\\"phase\\\":\\\"final_answer\\\"}\"\n            }\n          ],\n          \"api\": \"openai-codex-responses\",\n          \"provider\": \"openai-codex\",\n          \"model\": \"gpt-5.4\",\n          \"usage\": {\n            \"input\": 22844,\n            \"output\": 167,\n            \"totalTokens\": 23011,\n            \"cacheRead\": 0,\n            \"cacheWrite\": 0,\n            \"cost\": {\n              \"total\": 0.05961500000000001\n            }\n          },\n          \"stopReason\": \"stop\",\n          \"timestamp\": 1774794545611,\n          \"responseId\": \"resp_0720d1a20670abea0169c937335d588191b6290aca27e01140\",\n          \"__openclaw\": {\n            \"id\": \"9c1a98e3\",\n            \"seq\": 10\n          }\n        }\n      ]\n    }\n  ]\n}"}],"details":{"count":7,"sessions":[{"key":"agent:main:main","kind":"other","channel":"webchat","origin":{"provider":"webchat"},"deliveryContext":{"channel":"webchat"},"updatedAt":1774976496929,"sessionId":"b8591247-dd23-46f5-ba1c-b375a15ac131","model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","contextTokens":1000000,"totalTokens":15104,"estimatedCostUsd":0.117615,"status":"running","startedAt":1774976496261,"childSessions":["agent:main:subagent:81d7b77f-33c5-424a-adbe-10888ffd1690","agent:main:subagent:e3aae318-4f32-4b3e-a743-69796c328349","agent:main:subagent:6aa0098b-64ca-4e22-ae81-7b11e92f47c9","agent:main:subagent:bce133f4-39ae-4582-9c63-4ec2d5c0522e","agent:main:subagent:1fc1a793-e351-454b-9f47-7fced2298ca5","agent:main:subagent:edcb65a3-61e3-4a11-b36c-2db4f4d0292f","agent:main:subagent:49e325a0-4b0e-4c25-87d8-cf335ff114c3","agent:main:subagent:dc24faab-3aae-482a-a304-961eabe592a2","agent:main:subagent:0d8719eb-b287-49cd-ae2e-5b7f7a2e2551"],"systemSent":true,"abortedLastRun":false,"lastChannel":"webchat","transcriptPath":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\main\\sessions\\b8591247-dd23-46f5-ba1c-b375a15ac131.jsonl","messages":[{"role":"assistant","content":[],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"totalTokens":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"total":0}},"stopReason":"aborted","timestamp":1774976414464,"errorMessage":"Request was aborted","__openclaw":{"id":"0e608549","seq":6}},{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Summarize my recent sessions"}],"timestamp":1774976496260,"__openclaw":{"id":"05a9776b","seq":7},"senderLabel":"openclaw-control-ui"},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants a summary of their recent sessions. Let me use sessions_list to get recent sessions."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_01Kdd1oRw3wZjuQm59mcBdoF","name":"sessions_list","arguments":{"limit":10,"messageLimit":3}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"anthropic","model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","usage":{"input":3,"output":107,"totalTokens":20484,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":20374,"cost":{"total":0.0780165}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774976496466,"responseId":"msg_01LfRfXHew6rq5aShD4NxGca","__openclaw":{"id":"db52dda1","seq":8}}]},{"key":"agent:main:subagent:0d8719eb-b287-49cd-ae2e-5b7f7a2e2551","kind":"other","channel":"webchat","spawnedBy":"agent:main:main","label":"watchdog-mvp-reconciler","displayName":"webchat:g-agent-main-subagent-0d8719eb-b287-49cd-ae2e-5b7f7a2e2551","parentSessionKey":"agent:main:main","deliveryContext":{"channel":"webchat"},"updatedAt":1774877364780,"sessionId":"5011acc2-400b-4819-98ee-0dfa2ebbc124","model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","contextTokens":1000000,"totalTokens":85092,"estimatedCostUsd":1.1475174000000001,"status":"done","startedAt":1774876965842,"endedAt":1774877319530,"runtimeMs":344365,"abortedLastRun":false,"lastChannel":"webchat","transcriptPath":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\main\\sessions\\5011acc2-400b-4819-98ee-0dfa2ebbc124.jsonl","messages":[{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Let's do a final syntax check of all modified/created files:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"toolu_01H5SB34N3Juwgs94DXKZdVF","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\workspace; python -c \"import task_watchdog.reconciler; print('reconciler OK')\"\npython -c \"import ast; ast.parse(open(r'C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\workspace\\task_watchdog\\watchdog.py', encoding='utf-8').read()); print('watchdog syntax OK')\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"anthropic","model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","usage":{"input":1,"output":157,"totalTokens":85072,"cacheRead":83055,"cacheWrite":1859,"cost":{"total":0.03424575}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774877299253,"responseId":"msg_01WR3zQJjE3YtPUyPcSavrMd","__openclaw":{"id":"7b0d9898","seq":67}},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Everything is clean. Here's the complete summary:\n\n---\n\n## Entregáveis\n\n### 1. Diagnóstico\n\n**Problema raiz:** `watchdog.py` confia 100% em `active_tasks.json` sem consultar o runtime. O campo `status` só muda se o agente que lançou a task o actualizar explicitamente — o que não acontece quando a session termina silenciosamente ou é esquecida.\n\n**Caso concreto:** Task `retest_claude_code_sidecar_20260328_160800` estava como `running` há +2 dias. Em `subagents/runs.json` o run correspondente (`childSessionKey: agent:main:subagent:f45bf7bf...`) tinha `endedAt`, `endedReason: subagent-complete`, `outcome.status: ok`. A task estava morta mas gerava pings a cada 10 minutos.\n\n### 2. Estados mínimos implementados\n\n`spawned → running → stalled → orphaned` (escalada por tempo, sem runtime)  \n`running → completed / failed` (reconciliado contra `runs.json`)\n\n### 3. Implementação\n\n**Ficheiros criados:**\n- `task_watchdog/reconciler.py` — lógica de reconciliação (225 linhas). Lê `subagents/runs.json`, pesquisa por `childSessionKey`, classifica o run, e actualiza o status da task sem inventar infra externa.\n\n**Ficheiros alterados:**\n- `task_watchdog/watchdog.py` — `main()` chama `reconcile_all()` antes do `evaluate_tasks()`, com fallback silencioso se o reconciler falhar. `evaluate_tasks()` passou a suportar `spawned`, `stalled`, e `orphaned`. Deduplicação por `terminalNotifiedStatus` impede notificações repetidas.\n\n**Ficheiro de documentação criado:**\n- `task_watchdog/RECONCILER_NOTES.md` — diagnóstico, arquitectura, thresholds, notas de teste.\n\n### 4. Validado em execução\n\n- Primeira run: reconciliou zombie → `completed`, notificou uma vez, arquivou em `task_history.jsonl`, removeu de `active_tasks.json`\n- Segunda run: zero notificações falsas, `remaining: []`, `notifications: []`"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"anthropic","model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","usage":{"input":1,"output":580,"totalTokens":85672,"cacheRead":84914,"cacheWrite":177,"cost":{"total":0.034840949999999996}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774877303444,"responseId":"msg_011opKNjJThTq68XsUsabBjj","__openclaw":{"id":"5c002f29","seq":69}}]},{"key":"agent:main:subagent:49e325a0-4b0e-4c25-87d8-cf335ff114c3","kind":"other","channel":"webchat","spawnedBy":"agent:main:main","label":"session-pack-B","displayName":"webchat:g-agent-main-subagent-49e325a0-4b0e-4c25-87d8-cf335ff114c3","parentSessionKey":"agent:main:main","deliveryContext":{"channel":"webchat"},"updatedAt":1774794664275,"sessionId":"467b2bc4-8236-4d4e-bc56-1e5245b7802e","model":"gpt-5.4","contextTokens":272000,"totalTokens":31343,"estimatedCostUsd":0.1607745,"status":"done","startedAt":1774794484991,"endedAt":1774794639138,"runtimeMs":149383,"abortedLastRun":false,"lastChannel":"webchat","transcriptPath":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\main\\sessions\\467b2bc4-8236-4d4e-bc56-1e5245b7802e.jsonl","messages":[{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Drafting file plans**\n\nI need to focus on creating the file, maybe without added complexity. I might take a look at the existing document 23, just to see what's there and decide whether to overwrite it. It could be helpful to read through relevant documents too, but the user said “primarily,” so I’ll stick with the essentials. My goal is to draft a concise file that covers what the user needs effectively!"},{"type":"text","text":"Vou consolidar isto num pack operacional único, focado em sequenciamento real, decisões ao vivo e fronteiras Lucca vs Claude Code.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0f1f4c750ced0df40169c9370bf1748191b8c97773e0c2dfe9\",\"phase\":\"commentary\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_r3dMNoyhHTPQCuXZU7KriH5q|fc_0f1f4c750ced0df40169c9370c0be8819189ccea8a40b8832f","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\reviews\\tobias_review_29mar\\23_sector_execution_plan_B.md","content":"# 23 — Sector Execution Plan B (S4 + S5 + S6)\n\n## Purpose of this pack\nThis file is not another audit. It is a live implementation pack for Lucca + Claude Code.\n\nUse it during working sessions to decide fast, implement in the right order, and avoid rebuilding the wrong contracts.\n\nGuiding rule for all three sectors:\n- first freeze contracts that affect downstream sectors;\n- then implement deterministic substrate/helpers;\n- then implement operator flows;\n- do not let browser flows, prompts, or mirrors define architecture by accident.\n\n---\n\n# S4 — Asset Research\n\n## 1) Mission of the sector/component\nS4 exists to transform identified entities from S3 into usable editorial assets, stored locally with reliable metadata, provenance, and downstream usefulness. Its job is not only to find images/videos, but to convert raw search results into asset objects that S5 and S6 can consume without reinterpretation chaos. In practice, S4 is the bridge between semantic understanding of the story and concrete visual inventory.\n\n## 2) What is already solid\n- Sector concept is mature and one of the strongest in the architecture.\n- 1:1 mirror logic with S3 is good and operationally clean.\n- Separation between searchers and `asset_advisor` is correct.\n- API first, browser fallback is the right search strategy.\n- Local download with per-entity structure is correct.\n- `.jpg/.mp4 + individual .json` is stronger than one `metadata.json` per entity.\n- `how_to_use` as editorial bridge is useful if constrained properly.\n- Priority of searcher types is clear enough to start: character, location, vehicle/weapon first.\n\n## 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\n- Main contract conflict: individual JSON per asset vs old `metadata.json` residue.\n- Naming is not frozen: `b4_` vs `s4_`, `characters.json` vs `character_searcher.json`, slug styles mixed.\n- `tags` and `how_to_use` are too freeform if implemented as-is.\n- No hard dedupe policy yet: same image across sources, same entity, or near-duplicates.\n- License/commercial-use handling is not sufficiently formalized.\n- `asset_advisor` context contract is blurry: screenplay vs scene_bible vs entity excerpt.\n- Stock video handling is still underdefined for proof of license and account/platform traceability.\n\n## 4) Concrete implementation sequence\n1. **Freeze S4 canonical contracts before coding operators**\n   - decide `s4_` naming everywhere;\n   - kill official use of entity-level `metadata.json`;\n   - freeze slug convention;\n   - freeze asset JSON schema.\n2. **Freeze the per-asset JSON schema**\n   - include provenance, license, description, reasoning, tags;\n   - add structured `usage_flags`;\n   - keep `how_to_use` short and operational.\n3. **Implement deterministic S4 substrate**\n   - `download_asset`\n   - `image_metadata_writer`\n   - `video_metadata_writer`\n   - `asset_json_updater`\n4. **Implement minimum license + dedupe guardrails**\n   - basic license filter;\n   - dedupe via source URL + filename/hash + perceptual hash later if needed.\n5. **Implement P0 searchers only first**\n   - `character_searcher`\n   - `location_searcher`\n   - `vehicle_weapon_searcher`\n   - `stock_video_searcher` only if contract is frozen enough.\n6. **Implement `asset_advisor` after schema exists**\n   - read compact context, not full screenplay by default;\n   - enrich existing asset JSON rather than rebuild it.\n7. **Only then implement P1 searchers**\n   - event, artifact, atmosphere, era_context, map_diagram.\n8. **After first full pass, test S4 -> S5 handoff on one real video case**\n   - do not wait for all searchers to be perfect.\n\n## 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\n\n### SM-S4\n- [ ] Confirm canonical input from S3\n- [ ] Confirm output path and checkpoint naming\n- [ ] Dispatch only operators whose contracts are frozen\n- [ ] Track which entities still lack viable assets\n- [ ] Escalate license or source-policy blockers\n\n### character_searcher\n- [ ] Search authoritative sources first\n- [ ] Prefer identity clarity over aesthetic quality\n- [ ] Save local file per asset\n- [ ] Write individual JSON immediately\n- [ ] Mark canonical candidates explicitly\n\n### location_searcher\n- [ ] Distinguish historical vs contemporary views\n- [ ] Prefer establishing-shot usable assets\n- [ ] Mark period mismatch if uncertain\n- [ ] Save provenance clearly\n\n### vehicle_weapon_searcher\n- [ ] Capture exact model/variant when possible\n- [ ] Distinguish isolated object vs field usage\n- [ ] Mark uncertainty explicitly if model is approximate\n\n### event_searcher\n- [ ] Distinguish actual event imagery from generic campaign imagery\n- [ ] Mark documentary confidence\n\n### artifact_searcher\n- [ ] Distinguish original object, replica, scan, painting, blueprint\n- [ ] Preserve source context carefully\n\n### atmosphere_searcher\n- [ ] Only keep assets with real editorial use\n- [ ] Avoid pure moodboard noise\n- [ ] Tie use to expected scene/block intent\n\n### era_context_searcher\n- [ ] Tag context type clearly\n- [ ] Avoid vague “period feel” assets with no specific value\n\n### map_diagram_searcher\n- [ ] Check legibility at video use size\n- [ ] Mark fullscreen readability\n\n### stock_video_searcher\n- [ ] Save platform asset ID\n- [ ] Save source platform and license notes\n- [ ] Distinguish preview vs licensed final asset\n- [ ] Track subscription/account dependency if relevant\n\n### asset_advisor\n- [ ] Read only needed context\n- [ ] Add tags without repeating description verbatim\n- [ ] Write structured `usage_flags`\n- [ ] Keep `how_to_use` practical and short\n- [ ] Do not overwrite provenance/source fields accidentally\n\n## 6) Decisions Lucca must make live\n- Final canonical naming choice: **use `s4_*` everywhere?** Recommended: yes.\n- Final output naming convention: searcher outputs/checkpoints exact filenames.\n- Slug convention: hyphen vs underscore. Recommended: freeze one globally; likely hyphen for paths if already leaning there.\n- Minimum accepted asset JSON schema.\n- License policy: which licenses are acceptable per source/platform.\n- Whether stock video is P0 now or delayed until browser/license contract is cleaner.\n- Whether `asset_advisor` receives full scene_bible, per-entity excerpt, or per-block excerpt. Recommended: compact entity-relevant excerpt.\n\n## 7) What Claude Code can implement without waiting\n- JSON schema files for per-asset image/video metadata.\n- Deterministic metadata writers.\n- `download_asset` helper with retries and normalized file naming.\n- Basic asset JSON merge/updater logic.\n- Directory/path builders for canonical S4 structure.\n- Stubbed/checkpointed searcher IO contracts.\n- Initial dedupe utility using source URL + filename/hash.\n- License enum/normalization layer.\n- Test fixtures for one character/location/entity pack.\n\n## 8) What likely reuses from V3 vs net-new\n### Likely reuses from V3\n- Search source integration concepts.\n- Existing dataset-system download/search fragments.\n- Some API wrappers or source querying logic.\n- Possible local file handling patterns.\n\n### Net-new\n- Individual asset JSON contract.\n- `asset_advisor` enrichment model.\n- Structured `usage_flags`.\n- Formal dedupe layer for cross-source ingestion.\n- Clean S4 directory and checkpoint conventions.\n- Stock result normalization contract.\n\n## 9) First 3 concrete implementation tasks\n1. **Create and freeze `asset_metadata.schema.json` + `video_asset_metadata.schema.json` + naming convention note**.\n2. **Implement `download_asset`, `image_metadata_writer`, and `asset_json_updater` with tests on one entity folder**.\n3. **Implement one full vertical slice: `character_searcher` -> local asset save -> JSON write -> `asset_advisor` enrichment**.\n\n---\n\n# S5 — Visual Direction\n\n## 1) Mission of the sector/component\nS5 exists to transform a pile of scenes, entities, and available assets into a coherent visual plan for the whole video. Its job is not generating images and not searching assets, but deciding how the story should look over time: where visual blocks begin/end, which assets matter in each block, what moments require direct asset use versus AI generation, and what continuity rules must carry forward. It is the true visual decision layer of the system.\n\n## 2) What is already solid\n- The existence of S5 is architecturally correct and high leverage.\n- The 3-operator split is good: `narrative_segmenter`, `asset_matcher`, `visual_director`.\n- Parallel segmenting/matching and sequential directing makes sense.\n- Working at block level instead of scene-only level is the right choice.\n- `compiled_visual_brief.json` is the correct central artifact.\n- Sequential direction with memory is good if that memory is structured.\n- S5 correctly separates decision from S6 execution.\n\n## 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\n- Biggest risk: block/moment model vs old scene-based residues in mirror/docs.\n- `running_summary` can become opaque prompt glue if kept as prose.\n- `asset_matcher` still depends too much on weak/freeform S4 signals.\n- `keep_previous` is not fully contracted downstream.\n- Boundary between S5 and S7 motion/composition intent is still blurry.\n- There is still ambiguity whether matcher returns entities, assets, or both.\n- Segment boundaries may be semantically correct but visually wrong.\n\n## 4) Concrete implementation sequence\n1. **Freeze the official S5 output model**\n   - S5 decides by block and visual moment, not by raw scene output.\n2. **Freeze schemas before operator coding**\n   - block schema;\n   - kit schema;\n   - `running_summary.json` schema;\n   - `compiled_visual_brief.json` schema.\n3. **Clean old scene-level residues in mirror/docs/examples**\n   - especially context/tool examples that still imply scene-by-scene output.\n4. **Implement deterministic builders/validators first**\n   - `entity_index_builder`\n   - `kit_builder`\n   - `compiled_visual_brief_builder`\n   - `visual_brief_validator`\n5. **Implement `narrative_segmenter`**\n   - explicitly include visual-basis reasoning for splits.\n6. **Implement `asset_matcher` only after S4 structured flags exist**\n   - return entities and assets separately if needed.\n7. **Implement `visual_director` sequentially with structured summary state**.\n8. **Run one real end-to-end case across S4 -> S5 -> sample S6 inputs**.\n9. **Only after that, refine missing-entity escalation and repetition metrics**.\n\n## 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\n\n### SM-S5\n- [ ] Confirm S4 handoff contract is stable enough\n- [ ] Confirm S5 outputs are block/moment based\n- [ ] Ensure validators exist before large prompt iteration\n- [ ] Track unresolved `missing_entities`\n- [ ] Escalate downstream contract blockers to Lucca immediately\n\n### narrative_segmenter\n- [ ] Group scenes into visually coherent blocks\n- [ ] Consider not only theme/tone but visual universe changes\n- [ ] Record why a split exists visually\n- [ ] Avoid blocks that are too broad to direct cleanly\n- [ ] Avoid micro-block fragmentation without clear payoff\n\n### asset_matcher\n- [ ] Use structured S4 flags first, text second\n- [ ] Return matched entities and matched assets clearly\n- [ ] Report `missing_entities`\n- [ ] Separate direct-use assets from atmosphere/context support assets\n- [ ] Build compact kit per block, not a giant dump\n\n### visual_director\n- [ ] Process blocks sequentially\n- [ ] Read structured running summary, not essay-style history\n- [ ] Decide visual moments clearly inside each block\n- [ ] Mark decision type per moment (`direct_asset`, `ai_generate`, `composition`, `keep_previous`, `img2video` if applicable)\n- [ ] Emit executable downstream brief, not abstract taste language\n- [ ] Carry forward continuity rules explicitly\n\n## 6) Decisions Lucca must make live\n- Official S5 unit of planning: confirm **block + visual moment** as canonical.\n- Final schema of `compiled_visual_brief.json`.\n- Final schema of `running_summary.json`.\n- Whether matcher output is dual-layer (`matched_entities` + `matched_assets`). Recommended: yes.\n- Minimum and maximum block size heuristics.\n- Exact frontier with S7: what motion intent S5 is allowed to decide vs what S7 interprets. Recommended: S5 decides intention/type, S7 translates to TSX execution.\n- Formal reaction to `missing_entities`: requery S4, fallback, or proceed with generation.\n\n## 7) What Claude Code can implement without waiting\n- Formal JSON schemas for blocks, kits, running summary, compiled brief.\n- `entity_index_builder` from S4 outputs.\n- `kit_builder` and `visual_brief_validator`.\n- Data structures for block -> moments -> downstream decisions.\n- Structured `running_summary` updater.\n- Test harness with fake S4 assets and sample screenplay/scene_bible input.\n- Validators for path references, missing assets, invalid decision types.\n\n## 8) What likely reuses from V3 vs net-new\n### Likely reuses from V3\n- Very little direct reuse in architecture.\n- Some style-guide concepts and scene grouping intuitions may transfer.\n- Some downstream assumptions from old generation flows may inform field naming.\n\n### Net-new\n- Entire S5 sector logic.\n- Narrative block model.\n- Asset matching layer.\n- Structured running summary.\n- Compiled visual brief as canonical artifact.\n- Explicit `keep_previous` planning contract.\n\n## 9) First 3 concrete implementation tasks\n1. **Freeze and implement schemas for `block`, `block_kit`, `running_summary`, and `compiled_visual_brief`**.\n2. **Implement `entity_index_builder` + `kit_builder` using expected S4 asset JSON and flags**.\n3. **Implement one vertical slice: `narrative_segmenter` -> `asset_matcher` -> sequential `visual_director` for 1 real video excerpt**.\n\n---\n\n# S6 — Image Generation\n\n## 1) Mission of the sector/component\nS6 exists to execute visual decisions coming from S5 and convert them into actual image/video outputs or linked direct assets, with QA and normalized output manifests. It should be obedient, not interpretive. Its role is to take a structured visual brief, classify each moment, resolve whether it needs direct asset linking, AI generation, portrait canonization, or img2video, run the correct platform/tool flow, validate the result, and package outputs for downstream composition.\n\n## 2) What is already solid\n- Macro philosophy is correct: S6 executes rather than decides.\n- Separation between direct assets, AI generation, portrait canonization, QA, and img2video is good.\n- Mandatory `image_qa` is a strong architectural decision.\n- Portrait/canonical reference concept is correct.\n- Browser automation as a strategic layer makes sense if normalized properly.\n- Supervisor role around routing, quotas, and retries is conceptually sound.\n\n## 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\n- S6 is not contract-closed yet; it is the least operationally frozen of the three.\n- Browser skills per platform are still conceptual.\n- `prompt_builder` is still open and cannot stay open if implementation starts.\n- `portrait_manager` is underspecified; “single portrait” is likely insufficient.\n- `keep_previous` has a real handoff gap.\n- QA taxonomy/scoring is still too weak.\n- Platform fallback/retry behavior is not formalized.\n- Docs and mirrors still reflect old S6 structure in important places.\n\n## 4) Concrete implementation sequence\n1. **Do not start with browser automation first. Freeze S6 interfaces first.**\n2. **Freeze the S5 -> S6 intake contract**\n   - accepted decision types;\n   - fields required for each type;\n   - expected output manifest.\n3. **Freeze the internal S6 classification/output model**\n   - `visual_brief_classifier`\n   - `asset_linker`\n   - `prompt_builder`\n   - `platform_allocator`\n   - `image_qa`\n   - compiled output builder.\n4. **Resolve `keep_previous` explicitly**\n   - path resolution + inheritance behavior must exist before broader execution.\n5. **Define `prompt_builder` as a separate layer**\n   - deterministic/hybrid transformer from brief to platform payload.\n6. **Define browser-skill normalized contracts per platform**\n   - action list, inputs, outputs, error states.\n7. **Define `portrait_manager` as canonical pack manager**\n   - not just one portrait image.\n8. **Implement deterministic parts first**\n   - classifier, linker, prompt builder, allocator stubs, manifest builder, QA schema.\n9. **Only then implement one real browser runner for one platform**\n   - start narrow, not multi-platform.\n10. **Then add QA + retry loop on top of a single happy-path platform flow**.\n\n## 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\n\n### SM-S6\n- [ ] Confirm upstream visual brief version is canonical\n- [ ] Classify each moment into allowed execution types\n- [ ] Route to linker, generation, portrait, or img2video path\n- [ ] Track retries and platform choice visibly\n- [ ] Ensure every moment ends with materialized output or explicit failure reason\n\n### visual_brief_classifier\n- [ ] Classify moment type correctly\n- [ ] Handle `keep_previous` explicitly\n- [ ] Reject malformed or underspecified moments early\n\n### prompt_builder\n- [ ] Convert creative brief into executable platform payload\n- [ ] Build prompt + negative prompt + params\n- [ ] Respect platform capabilities and account config\n- [ ] Use canonical references if available\n- [ ] Avoid embedding platform-specific logic everywhere else\n\n### portrait_manager\n- [ ] Build canonical pack, not just one image\n- [ ] Preserve identity notes and reference usefulness\n- [ ] Track which pack is primary for downstream reuse\n- [ ] Mark uncertainty when likeness is weak\n\n### platform/browser runner\n- [ ] Use stable action contract (`login`, `upload_reference`, `generate_image`, `generate_video`, `download_result`, `check_quota`)\n- [ ] Return normalized output payload\n- [ ] Expose failure state clearly\n- [ ] Save platform/job identifiers\n\n### asset_linker\n- [ ] Resolve direct asset paths correctly\n- [ ] Resolve `keep_previous` safely\n- [ ] Copy/link according to chosen local strategy\n- [ ] Output normalized manifest entry\n\n### image_qa\n- [ ] Score fidelity to brief\n- [ ] Score artifacts\n- [ ] Score character consistency when relevant\n- [ ] Check format/resolution\n- [ ] Return retry recommendation and rejection reason taxonomy\n\n## 6) Decisions Lucca must make live\n- Confirm S6 starts only after S5 contract freeze. Recommended: yes.\n- Confirm `prompt_builder` is separate from browser skill. Recommended: yes.\n- Decide first platform for implementation. Recommended: one platform only for first vertical slice.\n- Decide whether portrait canonization outputs one primary + secondary pack. Recommended: yes.\n- Decide exact `keep_previous` semantics.\n- Decide minimal QA scoring schema and acceptance threshold.\n- Decide copy vs link strategy for local asset materialization on Windows.\n- Decide whether stock/browser platform credentials/licensing constraints are ready enough for real implementation now.\n\n## 7) What Claude Code can implement without waiting\n- `visual_brief_classifier`.\n- `asset_linker` with `keep_previous` handling.\n- `prompt_builder` data model and first deterministic transformer.\n- Normalized browser runner interfaces/types, even before real automation.\n- `platform_capabilities_registry` scaffold.\n- `s6_compiled_output_builder`.\n- QA result schema and rejection taxonomy.\n- Resolution probe and manifest validators.\n- End-to-end dry-run pipeline with mocked platform responses.\n\n## 8) What likely reuses from V3 vs net-new\n### Likely reuses from V3\n- Some local asset handling/copy routines.\n- Possible fragments of generation logic or prompt practices.\n- Some existing browser automation ideas if they exist informally.\n\n### Net-new\n- True S6 execution architecture.\n- `prompt_builder` as explicit layer.\n- `portrait_manager` as canonical pack system.\n- Normalized multi-platform browser skill contract.\n- QA scoring/taxonomy layer.\n- `keep_previous` execution path.\n- S6 compiled manifest/output contract.\n\n## 9) First 3 concrete implementation tasks\n1. **Freeze and implement the S6 intake/output contracts, including explicit handling of `keep_previous`**.\n2. **Implement deterministic core: `visual_brief_classifier`, `asset_linker`, `prompt_builder`, `s6_compiled_output_builder`, and QA schemas**.\n3. **Implement one narrow vertical slice on one platform: brief -> prompt payload -> mocked/real runner -> download -> QA -> compiled manifest**.\n\n---\n\n# Cross-sector implementation notes for the live session\n\n## Recommended working order inside this pack\n1. S4 contract freeze\n2. S4 deterministic substrate\n3. S5 schema freeze\n4. S5 deterministic builders/validators\n5. S4 -> S5 real sample handoff\n6. S6 interface freeze\n7. S6 deterministic core\n8. one vertical slice across S4 -> S5 -> S6\n\n## Anti-patterns to avoid in the session\n- Do not start by editing mirrors/examples before contract choices are explicit.\n- Do not start S6 with browser automation first.\n- Do not let freeform text fields replace structured flags/state.\n- Do not implement scene-based S5 outputs if block/moment is the intended architecture.\n- Do not postpone naming/path/schema decisions “for later”.\n\n## Practical rule for Lucca + Claude Code\nDuring implementation sessions, Lucca should make architecture and tradeoff decisions live; Claude Code should immediately encode those decisions into schemas, builders, validators, and one narrow tested vertical slice. That is the highest-leverage rhythm for these three sectors."},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\reviews\\\\tobias_review_29mar\\\\23_sector_execution_plan_B.md\",\"content\":\"# 23 — Sector Execution Plan B (S4 + S5 + S6)\\n\\n## Purpose of this pack\\nThis file is not another audit. It is a live implementation pack for Lucca + Claude Code.\\n\\nUse it during working sessions to decide fast, implement in the right order, and avoid rebuilding the wrong contracts.\\n\\nGuiding rule for all three sectors:\\n- first freeze contracts that affect downstream sectors;\\n- then implement deterministic substrate/helpers;\\n- then implement operator flows;\\n- do not let browser flows, prompts, or mirrors define architecture by accident.\\n\\n---\\n\\n# S4 — Asset Research\\n\\n## 1) Mission of the sector/component\\nS4 exists to transform identified entities from S3 into usable editorial assets, stored locally with reliable metadata, provenance, and downstream usefulness. Its job is not only to find images/videos, but to convert raw search results into asset objects that S5 and S6 can consume without reinterpretation chaos. In practice, S4 is the bridge between semantic understanding of the story and concrete visual inventory.\\n\\n## 2) What is already solid\\n- Sector concept is mature and one of the strongest in the architecture.\\n- 1:1 mirror logic with S3 is good and operationally clean.\\n- Separation between searchers and `asset_advisor` is correct.\\n- API first, browser fallback is the right search strategy.\\n- Local download with per-entity structure is correct.\\n- `.jpg/.mp4 + individual .json` is stronger than one `metadata.json` per entity.\\n- `how_to_use` as editorial bridge is useful if constrained properly.\\n- Priority of searcher types is clear enough to start: character, location, vehicle/weapon first.\\n\\n## 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\\n- Main contract conflict: individual JSON per asset vs old `metadata.json` residue.\\n- Naming is not frozen: `b4_` vs `s4_`, `characters.json` vs `character_searcher.json`, slug styles mixed.\\n- `tags` and `how_to_use` are too freeform if implemented as-is.\\n- No hard dedupe policy yet: same image across sources, same entity, or near-duplicates.\\n- License/commercial-use handling is not sufficiently formalized.\\n- `asset_advisor` context contract is blurry: screenplay vs scene_bible vs entity excerpt.\\n- Stock video handling is still underdefined for proof of license and account/platform traceability.\\n\\n## 4) Concrete implementation sequence\\n1. **Freeze S4 canonical contracts before coding operators**\\n   - decide `s4_` naming everywhere;\\n   - kill official use of entity-level `metadata.json`;\\n   - freeze slug convention;\\n   - freeze asset JSON schema.\\n2. **Freeze the per-asset JSON schema**\\n   - include provenance, license, description, reasoning, tags;\\n   - add structured `usage_flags`;\\n   - keep `how_to_use` short and operational.\\n3. **Implement deterministic S4 substrate**\\n   - `download_asset`\\n   - `image_metadata_writer`\\n   - `video_metadata_writer`\\n   - `asset_json_updater`\\n4. **Implement minimum license + dedupe guardrails**\\n   - basic license filter;\\n   - dedupe via source URL + filename/hash + perceptual hash later if needed.\\n5. **Implement P0 searchers only first**\\n   - `character_searcher`\\n   - `location_searcher`\\n   - `vehicle_weapon_searcher`\\n   - `stock_video_searcher` only if contract is frozen enough.\\n6. **Implement `asset_advisor` after schema exists**\\n   - read compact context, not full screenplay by default;\\n   - enrich existing asset JSON rather than rebuild it.\\n7. **Only then implement P1 searchers**\\n   - event, artifact, atmosphere, era_context, map_diagram.\\n8. **After first full pass, test S4 -> S5 handoff on one real video case**\\n   - do not wait for all searchers to be perfect.\\n\\n## 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\\n\\n### SM-S4\\n- [ ] Confirm canonical input from S3\\n- [ ] Confirm output path and checkpoint naming\\n- [ ] Dispatch only operators whose contracts are frozen\\n- [ ] Track which entities still lack viable assets\\n- [ ] Escalate license or source-policy blockers\\n\\n### character_searcher\\n- [ ] Search authoritative sources first\\n- [ ] Prefer identity clarity over aesthetic quality\\n- [ ] Save local file per asset\\n- [ ] Write individual JSON immediately\\n- [ ] Mark canonical candidates explicitly\\n\\n### location_searcher\\n- [ ] Distinguish historical vs contemporary views\\n- [ ] Prefer establishing-shot usable assets\\n- [ ] Mark period mismatch if uncertain\\n- [ ] Save provenance clearly\\n\\n### vehicle_weapon_searcher\\n- [ ] Capture exact model/variant when possible\\n- [ ] Distinguish isolated object vs field usage\\n- [ ] Mark uncertainty explicitly if model is approximate\\n\\n### event_searcher\\n- [ ] Distinguish actual event imagery from generic campaign imagery\\n- [ ] Mark documentary confidence\\n\\n### artifact_searcher\\n- [ ] Distinguish original object, replica, scan, painting, blueprint\\n- [ ] Preserve source context carefully\\n\\n### atmosphere_searcher\\n- [ ] Only keep assets with real editorial use\\n- [ ] Avoid pure moodboard noise\\n- [ ] Tie use to expected scene/block intent\\n\\n### era_context_searcher\\n- [ ] Tag context type clearly\\n- [ ] Avoid vague “period feel” assets with no specific value\\n\\n### map_diagram_searcher\\n- [ ] Check legibility at video use size\\n- [ ] Mark fullscreen readability\\n\\n### stock_video_searcher\\n- [ ] Save platform asset ID\\n- [ ] Save source platform and license notes\\n- [ ] Distinguish preview vs licensed final asset\\n- [ ] Track subscription/account dependency if relevant\\n\\n### asset_advisor\\n- [ ] Read only needed context\\n- [ ] Add tags without repeating description verbatim\\n- [ ] Write structured `usage_flags`\\n- [ ] Keep `how_to_use` practical and short\\n- [ ] Do not overwrite provenance/source fields accidentally\\n\\n## 6) Decisions Lucca must make live\\n- Final canonical naming choice: **use `s4_*` everywhere?** Recommended: yes.\\n- Final output naming convention: searcher outputs/checkpoints exact filenames.\\n- Slug convention: hyphen vs underscore. Recommended: freeze one globally; likely hyphen for paths if already leaning there.\\n- Minimum accepted asset JSON schema.\\n- License policy: which licenses are acceptable per source/platform.\\n- Whether stock video is P0 now or delayed until browser/license contract is cleaner.\\n- Whether `asset_advisor` receives full scene_bible, per-entity excerpt, or per-block excerpt. Recommended: compact entity-relevant excerpt.\\n\\n## 7) What Claude Code can implement without waiting\\n- JSON schema files for per-asset image/video metadata.\\n- Deterministic metadata writers.\\n- `download_asset` helper with retries and normalized file naming.\\n- Basic asset JSON merge/updater logic.\\n- Directory/path builders for canonical S4 structure.\\n- Stubbed/checkpointed searcher IO contracts.\\n- Initial dedupe utility using source URL + filename/hash.\\n- License enum/normalization layer.\\n- Test fixtures for one character/location/entity pack.\\n\\n## 8) What likely reuses from V3 vs net-new\\n### Likely reuses from V3\\n- Search source integration concepts.\\n- Existing dataset-system download/search fragments.\\n- Some API wrappers or source querying logic.\\n- Possible local file handling patterns.\\n\\n### Net-new\\n- Individual asset JSON contract.\\n- `asset_advisor` enrichment model.\\n- Structured `usage_flags`.\\n- Formal dedupe layer for cross-source ingestion.\\n- Clean S4 directory and checkpoint conventions.\\n- Stock result normalization contract.\\n\\n## 9) First 3 concrete implementation tasks\\n1. **Create and freeze `asset_metadata.schema.json` + `video_asset_metadata.schema.json` + naming convention note**.\\n2. **Implement `download_asset`, `image_metadata_writer`, and `asset_json_updater` with tests on one entity folder**.\\n3. **Implement one full vertical slice: `character_searcher` -> local asset save -> JSON write -> `asset_advisor` enrichment**.\\n\\n---\\n\\n# S5 — Visual Direction\\n\\n## 1) Mission of the sector/component\\nS5 exists to transform a pile of scenes, entities, and available assets into a coherent visual plan for the whole video. Its job is not generating images and not searching assets, but deciding how the story should look over time: where visual blocks begin/end, which assets matter in each block, what moments require direct asset use versus AI generation, and what continuity rules must carry forward. It is the true visual decision layer of the system.\\n\\n## 2) What is already solid\\n- The existence of S5 is architecturally correct and high leverage.\\n- The 3-operator split is good: `narrative_segmenter`, `asset_matcher`, `visual_director`.\\n- Parallel segmenting/matching and sequential directing makes sense.\\n- Working at block level instead of scene-only level is the right choice.\\n- `compiled_visual_brief.json` is the correct central artifact.\\n- Sequential direction with memory is good if that memory is structured.\\n- S5 correctly separates decision from S6 execution.\\n\\n## 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\\n- Biggest risk: block/moment model vs old scene-based residues in mirror/docs.\\n- `running_summary` can become opaque prompt glue if kept as prose.\\n- `asset_matcher` still depends too much on weak/freeform S4 signals.\\n- `keep_previous` is not fully contracted downstream.\\n- Boundary between S5 and S7 motion/composition intent is still blurry.\\n- There is still ambiguity whether matcher returns entities, assets, or both.\\n- Segment boundaries may be semantically correct but visually wrong.\\n\\n## 4) Concrete implementation sequence\\n1. **Freeze the official S5 output model**\\n   - S5 decides by block and visual moment, not by raw scene output.\\n2. **Freeze schemas before operator coding**\\n   - block schema;\\n   - kit schema;\\n   - `running_summary.json` schema;\\n   - `compiled_visual_brief.json` schema.\\n3. **Clean old scene-level residues in mirror/docs/examples**\\n   - especially context/tool examples that still imply scene-by-scene output.\\n4. **Implement deterministic builders/validators first**\\n   - `entity_index_builder`\\n   - `kit_builder`\\n   - `compiled_visual_brief_builder`\\n   - `visual_brief_validator`\\n5. **Implement `narrative_segmenter`**\\n   - explicitly include visual-basis reasoning for splits.\\n6. **Implement `asset_matcher` only after S4 structured flags exist**\\n   - return entities and assets separately if needed.\\n7. **Implement `visual_director` sequentially with structured summary state**.\\n8. **Run one real end-to-end case across S4 -> S5 -> sample S6 inputs**.\\n9. **Only after that, refine missing-entity escalation and repetition metrics**.\\n\\n## 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\\n\\n### SM-S5\\n- [ ] Confirm S4 handoff contract is stable enough\\n- [ ] Confirm S5 outputs are block/moment based\\n- [ ] Ensure validators exist before large prompt iteration\\n- [ ] Track unresolved `missing_entities`\\n- [ ] Escalate downstream contract blockers to Lucca immediately\\n\\n### narrative_segmenter\\n- [ ] Group scenes into visually coherent blocks\\n- [ ] Consider not only theme/tone but visual universe changes\\n- [ ] Record why a split exists visually\\n- [ ] Avoid blocks that are too broad to direct cleanly\\n- [ ] Avoid micro-block fragmentation without clear payoff\\n\\n### asset_matcher\\n- [ ] Use structured S4 flags first, text second\\n- [ ] Return matched entities and matched assets clearly\\n- [ ] Report `missing_entities`\\n- [ ] Separate direct-use assets from atmosphere/context support assets\\n- [ ] Build compact kit per block, not a giant dump\\n\\n### visual_director\\n- [ ] Process blocks sequentially\\n- [ ] Read structured running summary, not essay-style history\\n- [ ] Decide visual moments clearly inside each block\\n- [ ] Mark decision type per moment (`direct_asset`, `ai_generate`, `composition`, `keep_previous`, `img2video` if applicable)\\n- [ ] Emit executable downstream brief, not abstract taste language\\n- [ ] Carry forward continuity rules explicitly\\n\\n## 6) Decisions Lucca must\n...(truncated)..."}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":15549,"output":5121,"totalTokens":31294,"cacheRead":10624,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"total":0.11834350000000002}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774794498480,"responseId":"resp_0f1f4c750ced0df40169c93704301c8191bbea0274d86b09bf","__openclaw":{"id":"256c227f","seq":8}},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Done.\n\nCreated:\n- `C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\reviews\\tobias_review_29mar\\23_sector_execution_plan_B.md`\n\nWhat’s in it:\n- Practical execution pack for **S4, S5, S6**\n- For each sector:\n  1. mission\n  2. what is solid\n  3. what is ambiguous/dangerous\n  4. concrete implementation sequence\n  5. operator-by-operator checklist\n  6. live decisions for Lucca\n  7. what Claude Code can implement immediately\n  8. likely V3 reuse vs net-new\n  9. first 3 concrete implementation tasks\n- Final cross-sector working order and anti-patterns to avoid\n\nRelevant note:\n- I kept it implementation-oriented and contract-first, consistent with the audit + roadmap.\n- Where the source material is still unresolved, I marked the decision points instead of inventing certainty.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0f1f4c750ced0df40169c9378c099c8191a9631f41ccfabd09\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":239,"output":208,"totalTokens":31551,"cacheRead":31104,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"total":0.0114935}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774794633410,"responseId":"resp_0f1f4c750ced0df40169c9378b3ae08191a266deb99750d67d","__openclaw":{"id":"f924a590","seq":10}}]},{"key":"agent:main:subagent:1fc1a793-e351-454b-9f47-7fced2298ca5","kind":"other","channel":"webchat","spawnedBy":"agent:main:main","label":"session-pack-C","displayName":"webchat:g-agent-main-subagent-1fc1a793-e351-454b-9f47-7fced2298ca5","parentSessionKey":"agent:main:main","deliveryContext":{"channel":"webchat"},"updatedAt":1774794647014,"sessionId":"97af183b-f418-4a2a-8fd0-28b0a0d49d28","model":"gpt-5.4","contextTokens":272000,"totalTokens":30342,"estimatedCostUsd":0.1616375,"status":"done","startedAt":1774794483441,"endedAt":1774794634857,"runtimeMs":146741,"abortedLastRun":false,"lastChannel":"webchat","transcriptPath":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\main\\sessions\\97af183b-f418-4a2a-8fd0-28b0a0d49d28.jsonl","messages":[{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Crafting the file**\n\nI need to create a file, and I'm wondering if I should inspect the directory names first. But it seems like that might not be necessary. Instead, I think it's best to focus on writing something concise. I want to make sure that whatever I come up with is clear and to the point. I'm just going to push ahead with it!"},{"type":"text","text":"Vou consolidar os reviews num pack único de execução, já orientado para sessão live Lucca + Claude Code.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_03505f84b5d41c100169c93707520c8191b8725ee264b57166\",\"phase\":\"commentary\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_IurqUcPqzEBl1LY4895bmoQz|fc_03505f84b5d41c100169c937075c408191aa8c4bde1400e8d9","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\reviews\\tobias_review_29mar\\23_sector_execution_plan_C.md","content":"# 23 — Sector Execution Plan C (S7 + S8 + S9 + S10)\n\n## Purpose\nEste documento converte a auditoria de 29 Mar em material de execução prática para sessões live entre Lucca + Claude Code. O foco aqui não é teoria arquitectural; é: o que já está suficientemente fechado, o que ainda é perigoso, em que ordem implementar, o que decidir ao vivo e o que Claude Code já pode avançar sem ficar bloqueado.\n\nPrincípio operacional do bloco C:\n- primeiro estabilizar contratos locais do setor;\n- depois implementar substrate determinística / geradores / validadores;\n- só então ligar integração pesada entre setores.\n\n---\n\n# S7 — Scene Composition\n\n## 1) Mission of the sector/component\nS7 transforma decisão criativa estruturada em composição visual executável em Remotion. O papel do setor é receber contexto temporal e visual já decidido upstream, fazer planners escolherem animação, transições, composição e VFX em JSON canónico, e depois converter isso de forma determinística em `.tsx` seguros, validáveis e mergeáveis. É o setor que materializa a linguagem visual do vídeo sem deixar o LLM escrever o código final.\n\n## 2) What is already solid\n- O padrão central está correcto: agente decide, Python gera `.tsx`.\n- A separação entre planners e geradores técnicos está bem pensada.\n- `slim_jsons` por planner é uma boa decisão para reduzir contexto e acoplamento.\n- `NarrationLayer.tsx` determinístico no preprocessor é sólido.\n- Batching por ~12 momentos parece razoável para recovery e custo.\n- VFX como camada separada é uma melhoria real face ao V3.\n\n## 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\n- Há drift real entre spec e `workspace_mirror`.\n- Naming de skills ainda não está estabilizado (`*_tsx` vs builders/manifest flows).\n- Schemas divergem entre prompts e spec:\n  - `moment_id` vs `scene_id`\n  - `duration_ms` vs `duration_frames`\n  - `effect` vs `type`\n- Catálogos existem, mas o contrato de I/O não está congelado.\n- Não está 100% fechado se `animation_planner` usa vision ou só metadata.\n- Agregação do VFX por batch para layer global ainda precisa ficar explícita.\n\n## 4) Concrete implementation sequence\n1. Congelar naming canónico do setor:\n   - `narration_tsx`\n   - `animation_tsx`\n   - `transition_tsx`\n   - `composition_tsx`\n   - `vfx_tsx`\n   - `tsx_validator`\n   - `scaffolding_generator`\n2. Definir schemas canónicos dos 4 planners + exemplos mínimos válidos.\n3. Reescrever prompts do mirror para bater exactamente com os schemas congelados.\n4. Implementar validators de schema antes dos geradores TSX.\n5. Implementar `scaffolding_generator` + `narration_tsx` primeiro.\n6. Implementar `animation_tsx`, `transition_tsx`, `composition_tsx` com fixtures locais.\n7. Implementar `vfx_tsx` por último, já com regra explícita de merge global.\n8. Adicionar `tsx_validator` no fim do pipeline do setor.\n9. Testar geração end-to-end com 1 vídeo curto e 2 batches, não com caso grande.\n\n## 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\n- **animation_planner**\n  - schema canónico fechado\n  - catálogo final fechado\n  - naming de easing unificado\n  - input visual decidido\n- **transition_planner**\n  - catálogo final fechado\n  - naming alinhado com gerador TSX\n  - contrato de timing estável\n- **composition_planner**\n  - templates MVP fechados\n  - fronteira entre fullscreen/direct asset vs composition template definida\n- **vfx_planner**\n  - schema global + per-moment unificado\n  - regra de agregação batch -> layer global definida\n- **narration_tsx**\n  - input do S2 fechado\n  - output deterministicamente validável\n- **animation_tsx / transition_tsx / composition_tsx / vfx_tsx**\n  - parser de schema\n  - geração TSX estável\n  - imports consistentes\n- **tsx_validator**\n  - syntax\n  - imports\n  - faixas temporais básicas\n- **scaffolding_generator**\n  - `Root.tsx`\n  - `index.ts`\n  - base Remotion mínima\n\n## 6) Decisions Lucca must make live\n- O schema final canónico de cada planner.\n- Se `animation_planner` terá ou não acesso visual real.\n- O naming definitivo dos catálogos e easings.\n- Se haverá adapter layer temporária para conviver com prompts antigos.\n- Como VFX batch outputs viram `VFXLayer.tsx` global.\n- Se `moment_id` mata de vez `scene_id` neste setor.\n\n## 7) What Claude Code can implement without waiting\n- Estrutura base dos JSON schemas.\n- `scaffolding_generator`.\n- `narration_tsx`.\n- Skeletons dos geradores `animation_tsx`, `transition_tsx`, `composition_tsx`, `vfx_tsx`.\n- `tsx_validator` básico.\n- Fixtures e testes de parsing/geração.\n- Refactor do mirror para naming final, desde que a decisão canónica de nomes já esteja tomada.\n\n## 8) What likely reuses from V3 vs net-new\n**Reuse from V3**\n- `NarrationLayer` pattern\n- scaffolding Remotion\n- partes do batching/import merge\n- `tsx_validator`\n- parte de motion/transition infra\n\n**Net-new**\n- `vfx_tsx`\n- schema contracts mais rígidos por planner\n- separação formal planner -> TSX em toda a composição\n- eventual agregação estruturada de VFX global\n\n## 9) First 3 concrete implementation tasks\n1. Criar `schemas/` com contratos canónicos de `animation_plan`, `transition_plan`, `composition_plan`, `vfx_plan`.\n2. Implementar `narration_tsx` + `scaffolding_generator` e validar geração mínima de projeto Remotion.\n3. Reescrever os prompts do mirror de S7 para bater 1:1 com os schemas finais.\n\n---\n\n# S8 — Post Production\n\n## 1) Mission of the sector/component\nS8 transforma decisões de pós-produção em camadas de áudio e texto seguras para montagem final. O setor deve decidir música, SFX e lettering em nível semântico, resolver assets e parâmetros reais via camada determinística, e gerar `.tsx` reutilizáveis para soundtrack e overlays tipográficos, mantendo a fronteira crítica entre decisão criativa do LLM e resolução técnica de paths, volumes, timings e fallbacks.\n\n## 2) What is already solid\n- O princípio de segurança está muito bom: LLM escolhe nomes e intenções; resolver controla paths/volumes/durações.\n- Separação entre “o que” e “como” no lettering é a direcção certa.\n- `characters_already_letterized` resolve um problema operacional real.\n- `music_planner` global + `sfx_planner` stateless por batch é uma boa divisão.\n- A spec final está coerente com output `.tsx`.\n\n## 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\n- O mirror ainda fala em `engines` e JSON Remotion, não em skills TSX canónicas.\n- O lettering ainda está desalinhado entre spec e mirror:\n  - spec separa conteúdo e estilo\n  - mirror mistura tudo num planner só\n- Ownership de `SoundtrackLayer.tsx` entre S8 e S9 ainda não está totalmente fechado.\n- O prompt de SFX ainda carrega `trigger_timestamp_ms`, o que parece resíduo antigo.\n- Faltam schemas formais por fase: plano, estilo, resolução e output.\n\n## 4) Concrete implementation sequence\n1. Fechar naming final do setor:\n   - `audio_resolver`\n   - `music_tsx`\n   - `sfx_tsx`\n   - `lettering_tsx`\n2. Decidir explicitamente que S8 entrega componentes atómicos e S9 faz merge final do soundtrack.\n3. Separar lettering em duas fases reais:\n   - `lettering_planner` = conteúdo\n   - `lettering_style_planner` = estilo\n4. Remover responsabilidades antigas do planner de SFX (`trigger_timestamp_ms`).\n5. Criar schemas canónicos para:\n   - `music_plan`\n   - `sfx_plan`\n   - `lettering_content_plan`\n   - `lettering_style_plan`\n   - `resolved_audio_assets`\n6. Implementar `audio_resolver` primeiro.\n7. Implementar `music_tsx`, `sfx_tsx`, `lettering_tsx` com catálogos mínimos.\n8. Validar fluxo completo em caso simples com música + 3 SFX + 2 letterings.\n\n## 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\n- **music_planner**\n  - catálogo mínimo suficiente\n  - output sem path real\n  - volumes alvo definidos semanticamente\n- **sfx_planner**\n  - sem timestamp rígido herdado do desenho antigo\n  - output ancorável por palavra/evento\n  - política de skip/fallback explícita\n- **lettering_planner**\n  - decide só conteúdo/intent/placement lógico\n  - não escolhe detalhes técnicos cedo demais\n- **lettering_style_planner**\n  - decide fonte/cor/animação/entrada/saída\n  - respeita tipologia por conta\n- **audio_resolver**\n  - resolve nomes em assets reais\n  - injeta volumes/durações\n  - valida paths e existência\n  - faz fallback quando possível\n- **music_tsx**\n  - gera `MusicSections.tsx`\n- **sfx_tsx**\n  - gera `SfxLayer.tsx`\n- **lettering_tsx**\n  - gera `LetteringLayer.tsx`\n  - aplica fallback técnico de fontes quando necessário\n\n## 6) Decisions Lucca must make live\n- Se `SoundtrackLayer.tsx` é definitivamente responsabilidade de S9.\n- Se o lettering ficará formalmente em 2 operadores separados já nesta versão.\n- Se `trigger_word` substitui de vez `trigger_timestamp_ms`.\n- Quais campos mínimos entram em `MUSIC_CATALOG`, `SFX_CATALOG` e `FONT_CATALOG` no MVP.\n- Qual política de fallback quando não existir track/SFX adequado.\n\n## 7) What Claude Code can implement without waiting\n- `audio_resolver`.\n- Schemas do setor.\n- `music_tsx`, `sfx_tsx`, `lettering_tsx` skeletons.\n- Refactor do mirror de `engines` para `*_tsx`.\n- Split documental e estrutural do lettering em 2 etapas.\n- Fixtures locais de catálogo e testes de resolução.\n\n## 8) What likely reuses from V3 vs net-new\n**Reuse from V3**\n- `audio_resolver`\n- crossfade/music layering logic\n- parte da colocação temporal de SFX\n- wrappers/catálogos de áudio\n\n**Net-new**\n- separação formal conteúdo vs estilo no lettering\n- `lettering_tsx` com fallback multilíngue mais forte\n- contrato TSX mais limpo para entrega a S9\n\n## 9) First 3 concrete implementation tasks\n1. Criar os schemas canónicos de `music_plan`, `sfx_plan`, `lettering_content_plan`, `lettering_style_plan`, `resolved_audio_assets`.\n2. Implementar `audio_resolver` com fixtures reais/minimamente plausíveis de catálogos.\n3. Reestruturar o mirror de S8 para reflectir TSX outputs e lettering em duas etapas.\n\n---\n\n# S9 — Assembly + Render\n\n## 1) Mission of the sector/component\nS9 recebe as camadas produzidas por S7 e S8, valida integridade técnica e editorial, faz correções controladas antes do merge, monta a composição final do vídeo, compila, renderiza em chunks e produz o artefacto final pronto para finalização. É o setor de QA técnico-operacional e de integração final da camada Remotion.\n\n## 2) What is already solid\n- A ideia de revisão antes do merge está certa.\n- `tsx_validator` + reviewers + compile test + `render_fix` é uma boa defesa em profundidade.\n- `chunked_render` com retry e concorrência reduzida é pragmático.\n- `overlap_detector` como skill determinística é uma boa peça.\n- `audio_sync_checker` e `audio_levels_checker` fazem sentido como guardrails adicionais.\n\n## 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\n- É o setor com maior drift documental do bloco.\n- Set final de reviewers não bate entre spec e mirror.\n- Há contradição séria de resolução: vertical vs horizontal.\n- Naming dos outputs consumidos de S8 não está congelado.\n- `audio_sync_checker` e `audio_levels_checker` existem, mas ainda não têm checkpoint operacional claramente definido.\n- Não está fechado se reviewers devolvem patch estruturado ou editam TSX directamente.\n- O mirror ainda carrega restos de fluxo manifest-driven.\n\n## 4) Concrete implementation sequence\n1. Congelar reviewer set final.\n2. Congelar naming de todos os inputs TSX recebidos de S7/S8.\n3. Corrigir imediatamente a resolução canónica para 1080x1920 em todo o setor.\n4. Definir contrato de severidade por reviewer:\n   - warning\n   - auto-fix\n   - blocker\n5. Definir que reviewers não editam livremente; devolvem patch estruturado ou relatório accionável.\n6. Implementar `inventory/receipt validator` para garantir que tudo chegou antes de merge.\n7. Implementar `merge_layers`, `merge_soundtrack`, `generate_integration`.\n8. Implementar `compile_test`.\n9. Integrar `audio_sync_checker` e `audio_levels_checker` em checkpoints explícitos pré-render.\n10. Implementar `chunked_render` + retries.\n11. Deixar `render_fix` como último recurso, não como muleta para contrato mal fechado.\n\n## 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\n- **animation_reviewer**\n  - inputs mínimos definidos\n  - severidade definida\n  - não reescreve criatividade sem contexto\n- **transition_reviewer**\n  - valida timing e ritmo local\n  - política de blocker/warning definida\n- **composition_reviewer**\n  - resolução vertical corrigida\n  - safe areas definidas\n- **vfx_reviewer**\n  - precedence entre style guide, global e per-moment explícita\n- **music_reviewer**\n  - volumes, crossfades, paths\n- **sfx_reviewer**\n  - naming do ficheiro final estabilizado\n  - conflitos de densidade/repetição verificados\n- **lettering_reviewer**\n  - integra `overlap_detector`\n  - valida timing/legibilidade/posição\n- **tsx_validator**\n  - syntax/imports/basic timeline checks\n- **audio_sync_checker**\n  - checkpoint pré-render definido\n- **audio_levels_checker**\n  - checkpoint pré-render definido\n- **merge_layers / merge_soundtrack / generate_integration**\n  - naming final estabilizado\n- **compile_test**\n  - boundary test rápido\n- **chunked_render**\n  - 4 chunks + retry strategy\n- **render_fix**\n  - escopo cirúrgico, não genérico\n\n## 6) Decisions Lucca must make live\n- Reviewer set final canónico.\n- Se existe ou não `narration_reviewer`.\n- Naming final dos outputs de S8 consumidos aqui:\n  - `SfxLayer.tsx` ou `SFXComplete.tsx`\n  - `LetteringLayer.tsx` e/ou batches intermediários\n- Se reviewers devolvem patch estruturado ou ficheiro corrigido.\n- Em que checkpoint exacto correm `audio_sync_checker` e `audio_levels_checker`.\n- O que é blocker real vs warning não bloqueante.\n\n## 7) What Claude Code can implement without waiting\n- Correcção de resolução e limpeza do mirror/documentação do setor.\n- `inventory/receipt validator`.\n- `merge_layers`, `merge_soundtrack`, `generate_integration` skeletons.\n- `compile_test`.\n- `chunked_render`.\n- Estrutura de relatórios de reviewer com severidade.\n- `audio_sync_checker` e `audio_levels_checker` como skills determinísticas básicas.\n\n## 8) What likely reuses from V3 vs net-new\n**Reuse from V3**\n- `tsx_validator`\n- compile test\n- chunked render\n- parte do merge/import pattern\n- retry strategy\n\n**Net-new**\n- reviewer framework por especialidade\n- `overlap_detector`\n- integração explícita de audio sync/levels QA\n- inventory validator antes do merge\n- política formal de severidade\n\n## 9) First 3 concrete implementation tasks\n1. Reescrever o contrato canónico de S9: reviewer set, resolução, naming final dos inputs/outputs.\n2. Implementar `inventory/receipt validator` + `compile_test` + estrutura de relatórios com severidade.\n3. Corrigir o mirror/prompt do `composition_reviewer` para 1080x1920 e remover resíduos manifest-driven mais perigosos.\n\n---\n\n# S10 — Finalization\n\n## 1) Mission of the sector/component\nS10 fecha operacionalmente a produção: recebe o render final, valida o artefacto, comprime quando necessário, remove metadata, faz upload, actualiza tracking e compila o relatório final de produção. É o setor que transforma um render concluído em entrega operacional rastreável e auditável.\n\n## 2) What is already solid\n- O setor é simples e coerente.\n- O modelo “100% skills Python, supervisor só coordena” está correcto.\n- A sequência macro faz sentido: compress/strip -> upload -> tracking -> report.\n- Upload manual para YouTube nesta fase é uma boa contenção de risco.\n- `production_reporter` como fecho operacional é uma boa peça, desde que a ambição seja reporting básico.\n\n## 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\n- A convenção de checkpoints/directórios ainda diverge entre docs.\n- O mirror do setor está pouco materializado; há pouca estrutura concreta de execução.\n- Idempotência ainda não está fechada.\n- Não existe fonte única explicitamente definida para os 15 campos da sheet.\n- A claim de que monitoring ficou “coberto” é mais forte do que a arquitectura realmente garante.\n- A validação pré-upload parece leve demais para artefacto final crítico.\n\n## 4) Concrete implementation sequence\n1. Congelar convenção única de paths e checkpoints do setor, alinhada ao padrão global.\n2. Decidir artefacto único fonte de verdade para metadata final (`finalization_manifest.json` ou equivalente).\n3. Implementar validação pré-upload mais robusta.\n4. Implementar `compress_and_strip` com política de recompressão explícita.\n5. Implementar `drive_uploader` com idempotência mínima e recibo persistido.\n6. Implementar `sheets_tracker` com prevenção de duplicação/retry seguro.\n7. Implementar `production_reporter` lendo checkpoints já consolidados.\n8. Testar reruns parciais: upload repetido, sheet append repetido, report repetido.\n\n## 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\n- **compress_and_strip**\n  - recompressão condicional\n  - metadata strip obrigatório\n  - output path canónico\n- **drive_uploader**\n  - upload resumável\n  - recibo persistido\n  - idempotência mínima\n- **sheets_tracker**\n  - fonte única dos 15 campos definida\n  - append seguro\n  - release lock em ordem correcta\n- **production_reporter**\n  - checkpoints consumidos de forma estável\n  - output consolidado único\n- **video validator helper**\n  - tamanho > 0\n  - codec esperado\n  - duração válida\n  - presença de áudio\n\n## 6) Decisions Lucca must make live\n- Convenção final de checkpoints: globais ou locais do setor.\n- Estrutura final do diretório S10.\n- Qual artefacto será a fonte única dos 15 campos da sheet.\n- Regra exacta de idempotência para upload e tracking.\n- Quão forte será a validação pré-upload no MVP.\n- Como descrever honestamente a cobertura de monitoring vs reporting.\n\n## 7) What Claude Code can implement without waiting\n- `compress_and_strip`.\n- `video validator helper`.\n- `drive_uploader`.\n- `sheets_tracker`.\n- `production_reporter` skeleton.\n- Estrutura do `finalization_manifest.json`.\n- Testes de idempotência e rerun seguro.\n\n## 8) What likely reuses from V3 vs net-new\n**Reuse from V3**\n- `google_drive.py`\n- `google_sheets.py`\n- partes do fluxo ffmpeg\n- reporting/checkpoint reading parcial\n\n**Net-new**\n- `finalization_manifest` como contrato único\n- política explícita de idempotência\n- validação pré-upload mais robusta\n- fecho documental do setor em convenção global de artefactos\n\n## 9) First 3 concrete implementation tasks\n1. Definir e criar `finalization_manifest.json` como fonte única de metadata operacional final.\n2. Implementar `video validator helper` + `compress_and_strip` com outputs/checkpoints canónicos.\n3. Alinhar docs/mirror de S10 para uma única convenção de checkpoints e estrutura de diretórios.\n\n---\n\n# Cross-sector execution notes for the live session\n\n## Recommended live order\n1. Fechar contratos locais de S7.\n2. Fechar contratos locais de S8.\n3. Fechar naming/ownership exacto entre S8 -> S9.\n4. Só então travar S9.\n5. Fechar S10 já com outputs finais de S9 estabilizados.\n\n## Highest-risk live decisions\n- schema canónico de S7\n- lettering 2-step em S8\n- ownership do `SoundtrackLayer.tsx`\n- reviewer set + severidade em S9\n- naming final de `SfxLayer.tsx` / lettering outputs\n- idempotência e manifest final de S10\n\n## What should not happen in the session\n- Claude Code começar implementação pesada de S9 antes de naming/reviewer set/resolução estarem congelados\n- manter adapter implícito não documentado entre spec e mirror\n- deixar `trigger_timestamp_ms`, `scene_id` e naming antigo sobreviverem “temporariamente” sem decisão explícita\n- tratar `production_reporter` como substituto de monitoring activo completo\n\n## Practical rule for Lucca + Claude Code\nSe um ponto muda input/output, naming de ficheiro, schema, ownership ou checkpoint, isso é decisão de contrato e deve ser fechado ao vivo antes de codar em escala. Se um ponto é só execução determinística em cima de contrato já claro, Claude Code pode avançar imediatamente."},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\reviews\\\\tobias_review_29mar\\\\23_sector_execution_plan_C.md\",\"content\":\"# 23 — Sector Execution Plan C (S7 + S8 + S9 + S10)\\n\\n## Purpose\\nEste documento converte a auditoria de 29 Mar em material de execução prática para sessões live entre Lucca + Claude Code. O foco aqui não é teoria arquitectural; é: o que já está suficientemente fechado, o que ainda é perigoso, em que ordem implementar, o que decidir ao vivo e o que Claude Code já pode avançar sem ficar bloqueado.\\n\\nPrincípio operacional do bloco C:\\n- primeiro estabilizar contratos locais do setor;\\n- depois implementar substrate determinística / geradores / validadores;\\n- só então ligar integração pesada entre setores.\\n\\n---\\n\\n# S7 — Scene Composition\\n\\n## 1) Mission of the sector/component\\nS7 transforma decisão criativa estruturada em composição visual executável em Remotion. O papel do setor é receber contexto temporal e visual já decidido upstream, fazer planners escolherem animação, transições, composição e VFX em JSON canónico, e depois converter isso de forma determinística em `.tsx` seguros, validáveis e mergeáveis. É o setor que materializa a linguagem visual do vídeo sem deixar o LLM escrever o código final.\\n\\n## 2) What is already solid\\n- O padrão central está correcto: agente decide, Python gera `.tsx`.\\n- A separação entre planners e geradores técnicos está bem pensada.\\n- `slim_jsons` por planner é uma boa decisão para reduzir contexto e acoplamento.\\n- `NarrationLayer.tsx` determinístico no preprocessor é sólido.\\n- Batching por ~12 momentos parece razoável para recovery e custo.\\n- VFX como camada separada é uma melhoria real face ao V3.\\n\\n## 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\\n- Há drift real entre spec e `workspace_mirror`.\\n- Naming de skills ainda não está estabilizado (`*_tsx` vs builders/manifest flows).\\n- Schemas divergem entre prompts e spec:\\n  - `moment_id` vs `scene_id`\\n  - `duration_ms` vs `duration_frames`\\n  - `effect` vs `type`\\n- Catálogos existem, mas o contrato de I/O não está congelado.\\n- Não está 100% fechado se `animation_planner` usa vision ou só metadata.\\n- Agregação do VFX por batch para layer global ainda precisa ficar explícita.\\n\\n## 4) Concrete implementation sequence\\n1. Congelar naming canónico do setor:\\n   - `narration_tsx`\\n   - `animation_tsx`\\n   - `transition_tsx`\\n   - `composition_tsx`\\n   - `vfx_tsx`\\n   - `tsx_validator`\\n   - `scaffolding_generator`\\n2. Definir schemas canónicos dos 4 planners + exemplos mínimos válidos.\\n3. Reescrever prompts do mirror para bater exactamente com os schemas congelados.\\n4. Implementar validators de schema antes dos geradores TSX.\\n5. Implementar `scaffolding_generator` + `narration_tsx` primeiro.\\n6. Implementar `animation_tsx`, `transition_tsx`, `composition_tsx` com fixtures locais.\\n7. Implementar `vfx_tsx` por último, já com regra explícita de merge global.\\n8. Adicionar `tsx_validator` no fim do pipeline do setor.\\n9. Testar geração end-to-end com 1 vídeo curto e 2 batches, não com caso grande.\\n\\n## 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\\n- **animation_planner**\\n  - schema canónico fechado\\n  - catálogo final fechado\\n  - naming de easing unificado\\n  - input visual decidido\\n- **transition_planner**\\n  - catálogo final fechado\\n  - naming alinhado com gerador TSX\\n  - contrato de timing estável\\n- **composition_planner**\\n  - templates MVP fechados\\n  - fronteira entre fullscreen/direct asset vs composition template definida\\n- **vfx_planner**\\n  - schema global + per-moment unificado\\n  - regra de agregação batch -> layer global definida\\n- **narration_tsx**\\n  - input do S2 fechado\\n  - output deterministicamente validável\\n- **animation_tsx / transition_tsx / composition_tsx / vfx_tsx**\\n  - parser de schema\\n  - geração TSX estável\\n  - imports consistentes\\n- **tsx_validator**\\n  - syntax\\n  - imports\\n  - faixas temporais básicas\\n- **scaffolding_generator**\\n  - `Root.tsx`\\n  - `index.ts`\\n  - base Remotion mínima\\n\\n## 6) Decisions Lucca must make live\\n- O schema final canónico de cada planner.\\n- Se `animation_planner` terá ou não acesso visual real.\\n- O naming definitivo dos catálogos e easings.\\n- Se haverá adapter layer temporária para conviver com prompts antigos.\\n- Como VFX batch outputs viram `VFXLayer.tsx` global.\\n- Se `moment_id` mata de vez `scene_id` neste setor.\\n\\n## 7) What Claude Code can implement without waiting\\n- Estrutura base dos JSON schemas.\\n- `scaffolding_generator`.\\n- `narration_tsx`.\\n- Skeletons dos geradores `animation_tsx`, `transition_tsx`, `composition_tsx`, `vfx_tsx`.\\n- `tsx_validator` básico.\\n- Fixtures e testes de parsing/geração.\\n- Refactor do mirror para naming final, desde que a decisão canónica de nomes já esteja tomada.\\n\\n## 8) What likely reuses from V3 vs net-new\\n**Reuse from V3**\\n- `NarrationLayer` pattern\\n- scaffolding Remotion\\n- partes do batching/import merge\\n- `tsx_validator`\\n- parte de motion/transition infra\\n\\n**Net-new**\\n- `vfx_tsx`\\n- schema contracts mais rígidos por planner\\n- separação formal planner -> TSX em toda a composição\\n- eventual agregação estruturada de VFX global\\n\\n## 9) First 3 concrete implementation tasks\\n1. Criar `schemas/` com contratos canónicos de `animation_plan`, `transition_plan`, `composition_plan`, `vfx_plan`.\\n2. Implementar `narration_tsx` + `scaffolding_generator` e validar geração mínima de projeto Remotion.\\n3. Reescrever os prompts do mirror de S7 para bater 1:1 com os schemas finais.\\n\\n---\\n\\n# S8 — Post Production\\n\\n## 1) Mission of the sector/component\\nS8 transforma decisões de pós-produção em camadas de áudio e texto seguras para montagem final. O setor deve decidir música, SFX e lettering em nível semântico, resolver assets e parâmetros reais via camada determinística, e gerar `.tsx` reutilizáveis para soundtrack e overlays tipográficos, mantendo a fronteira crítica entre decisão criativa do LLM e resolução técnica de paths, volumes, timings e fallbacks.\\n\\n## 2) What is already solid\\n- O princípio de segurança está muito bom: LLM escolhe nomes e intenções; resolver controla paths/volumes/durações.\\n- Separação entre “o que” e “como” no lettering é a direcção certa.\\n- `characters_already_letterized` resolve um problema operacional real.\\n- `music_planner` global + `sfx_planner` stateless por batch é uma boa divisão.\\n- A spec final está coerente com output `.tsx`.\\n\\n## 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\\n- O mirror ainda fala em `engines` e JSON Remotion, não em skills TSX canónicas.\\n- O lettering ainda está desalinhado entre spec e mirror:\\n  - spec separa conteúdo e estilo\\n  - mirror mistura tudo num planner só\\n- Ownership de `SoundtrackLayer.tsx` entre S8 e S9 ainda não está totalmente fechado.\\n- O prompt de SFX ainda carrega `trigger_timestamp_ms`, o que parece resíduo antigo.\\n- Faltam schemas formais por fase: plano, estilo, resolução e output.\\n\\n## 4) Concrete implementation sequence\\n1. Fechar naming final do setor:\\n   - `audio_resolver`\\n   - `music_tsx`\\n   - `sfx_tsx`\\n   - `lettering_tsx`\\n2. Decidir explicitamente que S8 entrega componentes atómicos e S9 faz merge final do soundtrack.\\n3. Separar lettering em duas fases reais:\\n   - `lettering_planner` = conteúdo\\n   - `lettering_style_planner` = estilo\\n4. Remover responsabilidades antigas do planner de SFX (`trigger_timestamp_ms`).\\n5. Criar schemas canónicos para:\\n   - `music_plan`\\n   - `sfx_plan`\\n   - `lettering_content_plan`\\n   - `lettering_style_plan`\\n   - `resolved_audio_assets`\\n6. Implementar `audio_resolver` primeiro.\\n7. Implementar `music_tsx`, `sfx_tsx`, `lettering_tsx` com catálogos mínimos.\\n8. Validar fluxo completo em caso simples com música + 3 SFX + 2 letterings.\\n\\n## 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\\n- **music_planner**\\n  - catálogo mínimo suficiente\\n  - output sem path real\\n  - volumes alvo definidos semanticamente\\n- **sfx_planner**\\n  - sem timestamp rígido herdado do desenho antigo\\n  - output ancorável por palavra/evento\\n  - política de skip/fallback explícita\\n- **lettering_planner**\\n  - decide só conteúdo/intent/placement lógico\\n  - não escolhe detalhes técnicos cedo demais\\n- **lettering_style_planner**\\n  - decide fonte/cor/animação/entrada/saída\\n  - respeita tipologia por conta\\n- **audio_resolver**\\n  - resolve nomes em assets reais\\n  - injeta volumes/durações\\n  - valida paths e existência\\n  - faz fallback quando possível\\n- **music_tsx**\\n  - gera `MusicSections.tsx`\\n- **sfx_tsx**\\n  - gera `SfxLayer.tsx`\\n- **lettering_tsx**\\n  - gera `LetteringLayer.tsx`\\n  - aplica fallback técnico de fontes quando necessário\\n\\n## 6) Decisions Lucca must make live\\n- Se `SoundtrackLayer.tsx` é definitivamente responsabilidade de S9.\\n- Se o lettering ficará formalmente em 2 operadores separados já nesta versão.\\n- Se `trigger_word` substitui de vez `trigger_timestamp_ms`.\\n- Quais campos mínimos entram em `MUSIC_CATALOG`, `SFX_CATALOG` e `FONT_CATALOG` no MVP.\\n- Qual política de fallback quando não existir track/SFX adequado.\\n\\n## 7) What Claude Code can implement without waiting\\n- `audio_resolver`.\\n- Schemas do setor.\\n- `music_tsx`, `sfx_tsx`, `lettering_tsx` skeletons.\\n- Refactor do mirror de `engines` para `*_tsx`.\\n- Split documental e estrutural do lettering em 2 etapas.\\n- Fixtures locais de catálogo e testes de resolução.\\n\\n## 8) What likely reuses from V3 vs net-new\\n**Reuse from V3**\\n- `audio_resolver`\\n- crossfade/music layering logic\\n- parte da colocação temporal de SFX\\n- wrappers/catálogos de áudio\\n\\n**Net-new**\\n- separação formal conteúdo vs estilo no lettering\\n- `lettering_tsx` com fallback multilíngue mais forte\\n- contrato TSX mais limpo para entrega a S9\\n\\n## 9) First 3 concrete implementation tasks\\n1. Criar os schemas canónicos de `music_plan`, `sfx_plan`, `lettering_content_plan`, `lettering_style_plan`, `resolved_audio_assets`.\\n2. Implementar `audio_resolver` com fixtures reais/minimamente plausíveis de catálogos.\\n3. Reestruturar o mirror de S8 para reflectir TSX outputs e lettering em duas etapas.\\n\\n---\\n\\n# S9 — Assembly + Render\\n\\n## 1) Mission of the sector/component\\nS9 recebe as camadas produzidas por S7 e S8, valida integridade técnica e editorial, faz correções controladas antes do merge, monta a composição final do vídeo, compila, renderiza em chunks e produz o artefacto final pronto para finalização. É o setor de QA técnico-operacional e de integração final da camada Remotion.\\n\\n## 2) What is already solid\\n- A ideia de revisão antes do merge está certa.\\n- `tsx_validator` + reviewers + compile test + `render_fix` é uma boa defesa em profundidade.\\n- `chunked_render` com retry e concorrência reduzida é pragmático.\\n- `overlap_detector` como skill determinística é uma boa peça.\\n- `audio_sync_checker` e `audio_levels_checker` fazem sentido como guardrails adicionais.\\n\\n## 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\\n- É o setor com maior drift documental do bloco.\\n- Set final de reviewers não bate entre spec e mirror.\\n- Há contradição séria de resolução: vertical vs horizontal.\\n- Naming dos outputs consumidos de S8 não está congelado.\\n- `audio_sync_checker` e `audio_levels_checker` existem, mas ainda não têm checkpoint operacional claramente definido.\\n- Não está fechado se reviewers devolvem patch estruturado ou editam TSX directamente.\\n- O mirror ainda carrega restos de fluxo manifest-driven.\\n\\n## 4) Concrete implementation sequence\\n1. Congelar reviewer set final.\\n2. Congelar naming de todos os inputs TSX recebidos de S7/S8.\\n3. Corrigir imediatamente a resolução canónica para 1080x1920 em todo o setor.\\n4. Definir contrato de severidade por reviewer:\\n   - warning\\n   - auto-fix\\n   - blocker\\n5. Definir que reviewers não editam livremente; devolvem patch estruturado ou relatório accionável.\\n6. Implementar `inventory/receipt validator` para garantir que tudo chegou antes de merge.\\n7. Implementar `merge_layers`, `merge_soundtrack`, `generate_integration`.\\n8. Imp\n...(truncated)..."}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":14194,"output":5347,"totalTokens":30293,"cacheRead":10752,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"total":0.118378}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774794497147,"responseId":"resp_03505f84b5d41c100169c93702dfe08191bab8285fc3aeb168","__openclaw":{"id":"d8afe9b7","seq":9}},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Done.\n\nCreated:\n- `C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\reviews\\tobias_review_29mar\\23_sector_execution_plan_C.md`\n\nWhat’s in it:\n- Practical execution pack for **S7, S8, S9, S10**\n- For each sector:\n  1. Mission\n  2. What is already solid\n  3. What is ambiguous / dangerous\n  4. Concrete implementation sequence\n  5. Operator-by-operator checklist\n  6. Decisions Lucca must make live\n  7. What Claude Code can implement without waiting\n  8. Likely V3 reuse vs net-new\n  9. First 3 concrete implementation tasks\n\nRelevant note:\n- I kept it implementation-oriented and grounded in the reviews/roadmap only.\n- Main emphasis is on **contract freeze before heavy coding**, especially:\n  - S7 schema freeze\n  - S8 lettering split + soundtrack ownership\n  - S9 reviewer set / naming / resolution\n  - S10 idempotency + finalization manifest / checkpoint convention\n\nIf needed, the next natural step would be turning this into a **live session checklist version** or a **Claude Code task breakdown by file/module**.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_03505f84b5d41c100169c93784a60c8191b368f3984aa73f22\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":134,"output":268,"totalTokens":30610,"cacheRead":30208,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"total":0.011907000000000001}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774794621538,"responseId":"resp_03505f84b5d41c100169c9377f3be08191bafe959afe79afdd","__openclaw":{"id":"1c5b83f2","seq":11}}]},{"key":"agent:main:subagent:edcb65a3-61e3-4a11-b36c-2db4f4d0292f","kind":"other","channel":"webchat","spawnedBy":"agent:main:main","label":"session-pack-A","displayName":"webchat:g-agent-main-subagent-edcb65a3-61e3-4a11-b36c-2db4f4d0292f","parentSessionKey":"agent:main:main","deliveryContext":{"channel":"webchat"},"updatedAt":1774794630077,"sessionId":"31da92a9-1199-4822-935d-c35a51dd381e","model":"gpt-5.4","contextTokens":272000,"totalTokens":29796,"estimatedCostUsd":0.171842,"status":"done","startedAt":1774794484101,"endedAt":1774794621069,"runtimeMs":132049,"abortedLastRun":false,"lastChannel":"webchat","transcriptPath":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\main\\sessions\\31da92a9-1199-4822-935d-c35a51dd381e.jsonl","messages":[{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Looking at file production**\n\nI need to produce just one file, but maybe it would be helpful to inspect the directory structure to see if there's any existing V3 reuse. However, I'm not sure it’s strictly necessary; I could possibly infer what I need from reviews alone. Anyway, I need to focus on actually writing the file. I’ll make sure I have everything ready before I begin."},{"type":"text","text":"Vou converter a auditoria num pack operacional directo para sessão ao vivo: foco em ordem de implementação, checkpoints, decisões em aberto e o que Claude Code pode tocar já sem esperar.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0ecb2fb499bb29d00169c9370a3ca0819193559ce70828d620\",\"phase\":\"commentary\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_dTFQ7fL8FInic2Znk0ntOdEQ|fc_0ecb2fb499bb29d00169c9370a4d5481919796a637e1a33ae6","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\reviews\\tobias_review_29mar\\23_sector_execution_plan_A.md","content":"# 23_sector_execution_plan_A\n\nObjetivo deste pack: servir como material de execução ao vivo para Lucca + Claude Code. Baseado apenas nas reviews/docs auditadas em 29 Mar. Foco: PM, VO, S1, S2, S3. Princípio operacional: **não implementar em cima de contratos ambíguos sem primeiro congelar naming/schema/checkpoints mínimos**.\n\n---\n\n## PM — Production Manager\n\n### 1) Mission of the sector/component\nO PM existe para decidir **o que deve entrar em produção agora**. Lê a PUB + configs locais, calcula prioridade/runway, aplica overrides do Lucca/Tobias, escolhe canal/idioma, e produz um job JSON canónico para o VO. O papel dele não é executar pipeline nem improvisar lógica criativa; é transformar estado operacional disperso em uma decisão clara, auditável e consumível.\n\n### 2) What is already solid\n- Separação PM = decide **o que**, VO = decide/coordena **como**.\n- Lógica de runway e priorização já está conceptualmente clara.\n- Handoff PM -> VO já existe no desenho via job JSON.\n- Uso de YAML por conta/canal está bem estabelecido nos docs.\n- Papel do PM dentro da hierarquia nova já está razoavelmente claro no doc principal.\n\n### 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\n- `read_pub` continua não implementado; sem isso o PM não é operacional.\n- Mirror do PM ainda está preso a nomenclatura antiga (`branches`), o que pode induzir implementação errada.\n- Não há validador formal do job antes do handoff.\n- Política de falha está indefinida em casos reais: sheet inconsistente, datas mal formatadas, YAML inconsistente, falha parcial da API.\n- Fonte de verdade final ainda está ambígua se PUB e YAML divergirem.\n- Unicidade/idempotência de `job_id` está incerta.\n\n### 4) Concrete implementation sequence\n1. Congelar contrato canónico do job JSON do PM.\n2. Definir convenção única de naming/checkpoints/paths usados pelo PM.\n3. Implementar `read_pub` com normalização de datas e colunas.\n4. Implementar `job_builder` para converter canal escolhido + configs em job JSON.\n5. Implementar `job_validator` para validar schema, obrigatórios e consistência mínima.\n6. Testar PM com snapshots reais da PUB e 10+ casos representativos.\n7. Só depois ligar output do PM ao VO mínimo.\n\n### 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\n**PM supervisor / core logic**\n- [ ] Lê PUB real\n- [ ] Normaliza datas/colunas quebradas\n- [ ] Calcula runway ordenado\n- [ ] Aplica overrides deterministicamente\n- [ ] Resolve empate de prioridade\n- [ ] Escolhe canal final\n- [ ] Gera `job_id`\n- [ ] Produz job JSON canónico\n- [ ] Valida job antes de publicar\n- [ ] Escreve artefacto e log mínimo\n\n**read_pub skill**\n- [ ] Conecta à Google Sheets API\n- [ ] Lê colunas necessárias\n- [ ] Faz parse de `ULT PUB`, `PROGRAMAR`, `PROD`, `SCRIPTS`\n- [ ] Normaliza formatos inconsistentes\n- [ ] Retorna estrutura estável\n\n**job_builder skill**\n- [ ] Carrega YAMLs necessários\n- [ ] Monta payload final\n- [ ] Injeta paths/checkpoints/schema_version\n- [ ] Não inventa defaults perigosos\n\n**job_validator skill**\n- [ ] Campos obrigatórios\n- [ ] Tipos\n- [ ] Coerência de paths\n- [ ] IDs válidos\n- [ ] Erros estruturados\n\n### 6) Decisions Lucca must make live\n- Qual é a fonte de verdade final se PUB e YAML divergirem?\n- Em falha de leitura da PUB: abortar, usar cache, ou usar último snapshot válido?\n- `job_id` deve ser timestamp-based, UUID, ou composto por account/lang/date?\n- Qual critério exacto de desempate quando múltiplos canais empatam?\n- Quais overrides o Tobias/Lucca podem passar na v1 e qual formato canónico desses overrides?\n\n### 7) What Claude Code can implement without waiting\n- Schema inicial do job JSON.\n- `job_validator`.\n- Estrutura/base de `job_builder`.\n- Normalizador de row da PUB.\n- Fixture tests com exemplos simulados/reais sanitizados.\n- Cleanup do mirror do PM para remover linguagem antiga e alinhar naming.\n\n### 8) What likely reuses from V3 vs net-new\n**Provável reuse de V3**\n- Parte da lógica de priorização/runway, se já existia em scripts/utilitários.\n- Estruturas de config por conta/canal.\n- Qualquer wrapper anterior de Sheets, se existir.\n\n**Net-new provável**\n- Contrato formal PM -> VO.\n- `job_validator`.\n- Normalização robusta da PUB.\n- Política de erro/cache/fallback.\n- Convenção de output/checkpoints alinhada à arquitectura nova.\n\n### 9) First 3 concrete implementation tasks\n1. Criar `pm_job.schema.json` + exemplo canónico de job válido.\n2. Implementar `read_pub` com normalização e teste em snapshot real/sanitizado.\n3. Implementar `job_validator` e travar emissão de job inválido.\n\n---\n\n## VO — Video Orchestrator\n\n### 1) Mission of the sector/component\nO VO existe para transformar um job válido numa execução coordenada da pipeline. Ele inicializa diretórios/estado, faz fetch+lock do script, despacha setores na ordem certa, respeita dependências e paralelismo, consolida status, e fecha a corrida com report final. O VO não deve absorver ambiguidade estrutural dos setores; deve operar sobre contratos já congelados.\n\n### 2) What is already solid\n- Papel do VO como coração da execução está claro.\n- Sequência macro S1 -> S10 está bem definida.\n- Dependências principais já estão mapeadas, incluindo S2 + S3 em paralelo.\n- Responsabilidades de lock/report/cleanup já aparecem no doc.\n- Separação PM vs VO está madura.\n\n### 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\n- Workspace mirror do VO está ausente.\n- Contrato de invocação supervisor/setor ainda não está formalizado.\n- Error policy está vaga demais para automação segura.\n- Ownership de checkpoints, crash recovery e lock lifecycle continua indefinido.\n- Sem contracts estáveis, o VO só orquestra drift.\n- Se implementado cedo demais, cristaliza erros de naming e handoff.\n\n### 4) Concrete implementation sequence\n1. Não começar pelo VO pleno.\n2. Congelar primeiro contrato mínimo de dispatch/status/error/checkpoint.\n3. Criar `workspace_mirror/video_orchestrator/` alinhado com a arquitectura actual.\n4. Implementar `video_dir_initializer`.\n5. Implementar `script_fetch_and_lock`.\n6. Implementar `sector_dispatcher` mínimo viável para chamar um setor por vez com input/output canónicos.\n7. Implementar `checkpoint_resolver`.\n8. Implementar `final_report_builder`.\n9. Só depois adicionar retry taxonomy, pause/recovery e paralelismo real.\n\n### 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\n**VO core**\n- [ ] Recebe job validado\n- [ ] Valida pré-condições do run\n- [ ] Inicializa diretório do vídeo\n- [ ] Obtém script + lock\n- [ ] Escreve estado inicial\n- [ ] Despacha setores conforme dependências\n- [ ] Lê checkpoints/resultados\n- [ ] Classifica falha vs retry vs escalonamento\n- [ ] Consolida report final\n- [ ] Liberta lock e fecha run\n\n**video_dir_initializer**\n- [ ] Cria estrutura mínima de pastas\n- [ ] Escreve metadata inicial do run\n- [ ] Não sobrescreve corrida anterior indevidamente\n\n**script_fetch_and_lock**\n- [ ] Busca script certo\n- [ ] Aplica lock com owner claro\n- [ ] Detecta lock órfão\n- [ ] Retorna erro estruturado\n\n**sector_dispatcher**\n- [ ] Input canónico por setor\n- [ ] Execução mínima reproduzível\n- [ ] Capta output/checkpoint\n- [ ] Retorna status estruturado\n\n**checkpoint_resolver**\n- [ ] Encontra último estado válido\n- [ ] Decide resume vs restart\n- [ ] Detecta checkpoint incompleto/corrompido\n\n**final_report_builder**\n- [ ] Lista setores completos\n- [ ] Lista falhas/pendências\n- [ ] Resume artefactos gerados\n- [ ] Marca upload/tracking/script release quando aplicável\n\n### 6) Decisions Lucca must make live\n- Qual é o contrato mínimo de status por setor? JSON único, filesystem markers, ou ambos?\n- Quem é owner do lock do script em crash/recovery?\n- Em falha de um setor, o VO continua setores independentes ou pausa tudo?\n- Qual taxonomia canónica de erros da v1?\n- O VO v1 vai suportar paralelismo real ou apenas sequência + pontos paralelizáveis controlados?\n\n### 7) What Claude Code can implement without waiting\n- Estrutura inicial do mirror do VO.\n- Schemas de `sector_dispatch_request`, `sector_result`, `run_status`, `structured_error`.\n- `video_dir_initializer`.\n- `final_report_builder`.\n- `checkpoint_resolver` mínimo.\n- Skeleton de `sector_dispatcher` com interface estável, mesmo que alguns setores ainda sejam stubs.\n\n### 8) What likely reuses from V3 vs net-new\n**Provável reuse de V3**\n- Parte da lógica de bootstrap de diretório do vídeo.\n- Possível lógica anterior de lock/fetch de script.\n- Estruturas de report final/estado de produção, se existirem.\n\n**Net-new provável**\n- Mirror do VO.\n- Contrato formal entre VO e supervisores.\n- Taxonomia estruturada de erros/retries.\n- Recovery/checkpoint ownership alinhado ao sistema novo.\n\n### 9) First 3 concrete implementation tasks\n1. Criar schema de dispatch/status/error/checkpoint do VO.\n2. Implementar `video_dir_initializer` + `final_report_builder` mínimos.\n3. Criar mirror do VO e um `sector_dispatcher` stub com interface canónica.\n\n---\n\n## S1 — Pre-Production\n\n### 1) Mission of the sector/component\nS1 existe para transformar o script bruto num pacote fundador confiável para o resto da pipeline: screenplay preservado, texto polido para TTS sem degradar sentido, e `scene_bible` inicial com direção visual útil. É o setor que fixa a base narrativa/estrutural; se ele errar, os setores seguintes só amplificam erro.\n\n### 2) What is already solid\n- S1 é um dos setores mais fortes conceptualmente.\n- `scene_director` está bem pensado e com filosofia criativa sólida.\n- Estrutura supervisor + operadores + skills já está razoavelmente madura no doc.\n- Ideia de validação determinística + correção cirúrgica está correcta.\n- `tts_polish` já aparece melhor definido do que antes.\n\n### 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\n- Validators continuam blockers reais (`screenplay_validator`, `polish_validator`).\n- Mirror está desalinhado do doc oficial.\n- Checkpoints divergem (`b1_` vs `s1_`).\n- Mirror simplifica demais outputs e pode induzir implementação incompleta.\n- CLI/comandos do mirror parecem pseudo-interface não validada.\n- Schema do `scene_bible` ainda não está formalizado o suficiente.\n\n### 4) Concrete implementation sequence\n1. Escolher convenção canónica: `s1_` ou `b1_` e congelar.\n2. Congelar schema mínimo do `scene_bible.json` inicial.\n3. Implementar `screenplay_validator`.\n4. Implementar `polish_validator`.\n5. Reescrever mirror de S1 alinhado ao doc oficial.\n6. Formalizar feedback loop supervisor <-> operador por cena.\n7. Testar S1 ponta a ponta com 2-3 scripts reais longos.\n\n### 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\n**SM-S1**\n- [ ] Carrega script/job/contexto\n- [ ] Divide fluxo por cenas/segmentos conforme contrato\n- [ ] Chama operadores na ordem certa\n- [ ] Usa validators antes de aprovar output\n- [ ] Faz correção cirúrgica quando falhar\n- [ ] Escreve checkpoints consistentes\n- [ ] Escala após limite de falhas\n\n**scene_director**\n- [ ] Mantém fidelidade ao áudio\n- [ ] Produz `visual_direction` útil e acionável\n- [ ] Não inventa estrutura fora do script\n- [ ] Retorna formato canónico por cena\n\n**tts_polish**\n- [ ] Respeita YAML por idioma\n- [ ] Melhora oralidade sem mudar sentido\n- [ ] Não apaga informação factual\n- [ ] Retorna diff/estrutura rastreável quando possível\n\n**scene_bible_builder**\n- [ ] Cria `scene_bible.json` inicial\n- [ ] Inclui campos reservados para setores futuros\n- [ ] Mantém schema estável\n- [ ] Não mistura responsabilidades de setores seguintes\n\n**screenplay_validator**\n- [ ] Confirma preservação do conteúdo narrado\n- [ ] Detecta omissões/adições indevidas\n- [ ] Retorna erro específico por cena\n\n**polish_validator**\n- [ ] Confirma que polish não degradou sentido\n- [ ] Marca alterações perigosas\n- [ ] Retorna feedback utilizável para retry\n\n### 6) Decisions Lucca must make live\n- Convenção final de checkpoints/artefactos de S1: `s1_` ou `b1_`?\n- Qual é o schema mínimo obrigatório do `scene_bible` inicial na v1?\n- O output de `tts_polish` deve guardar texto final apenas ou também diff/metadados?\n- Qual critério mínimo torna `visual_direction` “bom o suficiente” para seguir?\n\n### 7) What Claude Code can implement without waiting\n- `screenplay_validator`.\n- `polish_validator`.\n- Schema inicial do `scene_bible.json`.\n- Reescrita do mirror de S1 para remover drift e pseudo-comandos.\n- Fixtures/testes para scripts curtos e longos.\n\n### 8) What likely reuses from V3 vs net-new\n**Provável reuse de V3**\n- Lógica anterior de segmentação/cenas, se existir.\n- Partes de prompts/regras do `scene_director`.\n- Possível estrutura inicial do scene bible.\n\n**Net-new provável**\n- Validators robustos.\n- Contrato formal do `scene_bible` na arquitectura actual.\n- Feedback loop supervisor/operador.\n- Limpeza completa do mirror para nomenclatura nova.\n\n### 9) First 3 concrete implementation tasks\n1. Definir e escrever `scene_bible.initial.schema.json`.\n2. Implementar `screenplay_validator` com testes de preservação de conteúdo.\n3. Unificar naming/checkpoints do S1 e reescrever o mirror em cima disso.\n\n---\n\n## S2 — Audio\n\n### 1) Mission of the sector/component\nS2 existe para transformar o texto aprovado em áudio útil para produção: gerar TTS, transcrever o resultado, alinhar script com timestamps reais e escrever isso no `scene_bible` de forma determinística. É o setor que converte narrativa textual em timeline utilizável downstream.\n\n### 2) What is already solid\n- A direcção nova com `audio_transcriber` + `timestamp_aligner` é melhor do que a versão antiga.\n- O problema real de alinhamento foi reconhecido explicitamente.\n- Retry por cena continua uma boa decisão estrutural.\n- `bible_updater` como skill determinística é uma decisão correcta.\n- A ideia geral do setor é tecnicamente sólida.\n\n### 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\n- S2 está em duas versões ao mesmo tempo: doc oficial vs mirror.\n- `timing_extractor` vs `timestamp_aligner` ainda não foi resolvido canonicamente.\n- `b2_audio` vs `s2_audio` quebra integração.\n- Checkpoints `b2_` vs `s2_` também divergem.\n- `tts_generator` continua crítico e não implementado.\n- KMS/wrapper de TTS e política PT->ES continuam frágeis/indefinidos.\n- `bible_updater` sem locking/atomicidade pode corromper estado partilhado.\n\n### 4) Concrete implementation sequence\n1. Escolher versão canónica de S2 e matar a outra.\n2. Congelar naming de paths/checkpoints (`s2_` ou `b2_`; `s2_audio` ou `b2_audio`).\n3. Formalizar schema do output de áudio/transcrição/alignment.\n4. Implementar `tts_generator` wrapper.\n5. Implementar `audio_transcriber`.\n6. Implementar `timestamp_aligner`.\n7. Implementar `bible_updater` com contrato de write seguro.\n8. Só depois endurecer `audio_validator` e confidence scoring.\n\n### 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\n**SM-S2**\n- [ ] Recebe cenas/texto final\n- [ ] Coordena geração por cena\n- [ ] Aciona validação/retry por cena\n- [ ] Escreve checkpoints consistentes\n- [ ] Atualiza estado final do setor\n\n**tts_generator**\n- [ ] Recebe texto/cfg de voz corretos\n- [ ] Gera áudio por cena\n- [ ] Salva manifesto/output estável\n- [ ] Retorna erro estruturado quando voz/model falhar\n\n**audio_transcriber**\n- [ ] Transcreve áudio gerado\n- [ ] Retorna palavras/timestamps brutos\n- [ ] Expõe métricas mínimas de qualidade\n\n**timestamp_aligner**\n- [ ] Alinha script final com transcript real\n- [ ] Produz timestamps por cena/trecho\n- [ ] Expõe confidence/erros de alignment quando possível\n\n**audio_validator**\n- [ ] Calcula ratio/semelhança\n- [ ] Decide auto-approve vs revisão\n- [ ] Isola cenas problemáticas\n\n**bible_updater**\n- [ ] Escreve updates no `scene_bible`\n- [ ] Mantém atomicidade mínima\n- [ ] Não corrompe dados de outros setores\n- [ ] Regista versão/update aplicado\n\n### 6) Decisions Lucca must make live\n- Qual é a versão canónica de S2: manter `timestamp_aligner` como substituto definitivo de `timing_extractor`?\n- Naming final de paths/checkpoints: `s2_*` ou `b2_*`?\n- Qual é o provider/contrato final da v1 de TTS?\n- Qual nível de confidence mínimo aceita alignment automático?\n- `audio_validator` entra na v1 ou pode ser simplificado primeiro?\n\n### 7) What Claude Code can implement without waiting\n- Unificação doc/mirror de S2 numa única versão.\n- Schema de outputs de transcrição/alignment.\n- `bible_updater`.\n- Skeleton de `timestamp_aligner`.\n- Wrapper de WhisperX.\n- Test harness com cenas sintéticas e reais.\n\n### 8) What likely reuses from V3 vs net-new\n**Provável reuse de V3**\n- Lógica de alignment/timestamping mencionada na review.\n- Partes de TTS/transcrição já usadas antes.\n- Estrutura de outputs de áudio, se já existia.\n\n**Net-new provável**\n- `bible_updater` como infra formal.\n- Contrato canónico do setor unificado.\n- Confidence/alignment validation mais explícita.\n- Locking/atomicidade de escrita no `scene_bible`.\n\n### 9) First 3 concrete implementation tasks\n1. Decidir e aplicar uma única versão canónica de S2 em doc + mirror + paths.\n2. Implementar `bible_updater` com write seguro no `scene_bible`.\n3. Implementar `timestamp_aligner` mínimo com testes reais de alinhamento.\n\n---\n\n## S3 — Visual Planning\n\n### 1) Mission of the sector/component\nS3 existe para extrair do script e do contexto as entidades visuais que tornam a pesquisa e a composição possíveis: personagens, locais, veículos, eventos, atmosfera, era, etc. O valor real de S3 não é “achar coisas interessantes”; é produzir entidades **buscáveis, consistentes e úteis** para S4/S5.\n\n### 2) What is already solid\n- A ambição e especialização do setor fazem sentido.\n- Supervisor de S3 melhorou operacionalmente com defaults, batching e formato compilado melhor.\n- `source_identifier` e `compiled_entities.json` ajudam rastreabilidade.\n- A divisão em identificadores especializados continua uma boa aposta.\n- O setor já aponta para outputs relativamente estruturados.\n\n### 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\n- Dedupe continua fraca.\n- Searchability real dos `search_hints` não está validada.\n- `atmosphere_identifier` tem alto upside, mas alto risco de produzir coisa bonita e pouco acionável.\n- Escolha de modelo ainda está pendente.\n- Não há validador formal suficientemente forte antes da compilação final.\n- `entity_focus` é central, mas o contrato com style/config ainda não parece totalmente congelado.\n- Overlap entre identificadores ainda pode produzir ruído e inconsistência.\n\n### 4) Concrete implementation sequence\n1. Congelar schema canónico de output por identificador + `compiled_entities.json`.\n2. Implementar `entity_output_validator`.\n3. Implementar `entity_deduplicator` como skill separada.\n4. Implementar `searchability_scorer` mínimo.\n5. Definir modelo canónico da v1.\n6. Só depois endurecer atmosphere/era/cross-consistency.\n7. Testar S3 contra 2 tipos de conta: histórica e não histórica.\n\n### 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\n**SM-S3**\n- [ ] Lê `entity_focus`/config\n- [ ] Ativa só identificadores necessários\n- [ ] Faz batching em scripts longos\n- [ ] Consolida outputs parciais\n- [ ] Corre validação e dedupe antes de compilar\n- [ ] Escreve `compiled_entities.json`\n\n**character_identifier**\n- [ ] Representa personagens explícitos e implícitos com cautela\n- [ ] Não força identidade sem base suficiente\n- [ ] Expõe ambiguidade quando necessário\n\n**location_identifier**\n- [ ] Produz nome/localização buscável\n- [ ] Preserva contexto histórico/geográfico útil\n\n**vehicle_weapon_identifier**\n- [ ] Identifica variante quando possível\n- [ ] Não inventa precisão falsa\n\n**event_identifier**\n- [ ] Isola eventos realmente relevantes para visual planning\n- [ ] Não duplica location/era sem necessidade\n\n**artifact_identifier**\n- [ ] Extrai objetos visuais realmente úteis\n- [ ] Evita overlap desnecessário\n\n**atmosphere_identifier**\n- [ ] Produz atmosfera acionável, não só literária\n- [ ] Gera hints buscáveis\n- [ ] Não invade papel futuro de S5\n\n**era_context_identifier**\n- [ ] Dá contexto temporal útil\n- [ ] Evita scope inflation\n\n**map_diagram_identifier**\n- [ ] Só gera quando houver utilidade real\n- [ ] Não polui output final com baixa relevância\n\n**entity_output_validator**\n- [ ] Valida schema por identificador\n- [ ] Campos obrigatórios/tipos\n- [ ] Consistência mínima do output\n\n**entity_deduplicator**\n- [ ] Resolve duplicados de forma menos simplista\n- [ ] Mantém rastreabilidade do merge\n- [ ] Não apaga informação útil\n\n**searchability_scorer**\n- [ ] Mede se hints são realmente pesquisáveis\n- [ ] Marca outputs bonitos porém impráticos\n\n### 6) Decisions Lucca must make live\n- Qual modelo entra na v1 canónica de S3?\n- Quais identificadores são obrigatórios na v1 e quais podem ficar opcionais?\n- Como representar ambiguidade/confiança para entidades implícitas?\n- O que torna um `search_hint` bom o suficiente para seguir para S4?\n- Até onde `atmosphere_identifier` pode ir sem colidir com S5?\n\n### 7) What Claude Code can implement without waiting\n- Schemas por identificador.\n- `entity_output_validator`.\n- `entity_deduplicator`.\n- Estrutura/base de `searchability_scorer`.\n- Test corpus pequeno para medir dedupe/searchability.\n- Cleanup do mirror para tornar defaults/compiled format canónicos.\n\n### 8) What likely reuses from V3 vs net-new\n**Provável reuse de V3**\n- Alguns identificadores e heurísticas de extração.\n- Possível lógica anterior de entidades/hints.\n- Parte da estrutura compilada, se já existia.\n\n**Net-new provável**\n- Dedupe séria como skill própria.\n- Searchability scoring explícito.\n- Representation de ambiguidade/confiança.\n- Hardening da camada de validação antes de S4.\n\n### 9) First 3 concrete implementation tasks\n1. Escrever schemas canónicos de outputs por identificador + `compiled_entities.json`.\n2. Implementar `entity_output_validator`.\n3. Implementar `entity_deduplicator` e testar com casos de overlap reais.\n\n---\n\n## Ordem prática sugerida para as sessões ao vivo\n1. **Freeze curto de naming/schema/checkpoints** só para PM + VO + S1 + S2 + S3.\n2. **PM substrate**: `read_pub` -> `job_builder` -> `job_validator`.\n3. **Shared infra mínima**: schema validation, checkpoint contract, `scene_bible` write contract.\n4. **S1 first**: validators + schema do `scene_bible` inicial.\n5. **S2 second**: unificar versão -> `bible_updater` -> alignment mínimo.\n6. **S3 hardening**: validator -> dedupe -> searchability.\n7. **VO mínimo** só depois dos contratos acima existirem de verdade.\n\n## Regra de ouro para Lucca + Claude Code\nSempre que houver conflito entre doc central, doc de setor e mirror: **parar, escolher versão canónica explicitamente, documentar e só então implementar**. O maior risco actual não é incapacidade técnica; é implementar a versão errada do sistema."},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\reviews\\\\tobias_review_29mar\\\\23_sector_execution_plan_A.md\",\"content\":\"# 23_sector_execution_plan_A\\n\\nObjetivo deste pack: servir como material de execução ao vivo para Lucca + Claude Code. Baseado apenas nas reviews/docs auditadas em 29 Mar. Foco: PM, VO, S1, S2, S3. Princípio operacional: **não implementar em cima de contratos ambíguos sem primeiro congelar naming/schema/checkpoints mínimos**.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## PM — Production Manager\\n\\n### 1) Mission of the sector/component\\nO PM existe para decidir **o que deve entrar em produção agora**. Lê a PUB + configs locais, calcula prioridade/runway, aplica overrides do Lucca/Tobias, escolhe canal/idioma, e produz um job JSON canónico para o VO. O papel dele não é executar pipeline nem improvisar lógica criativa; é transformar estado operacional disperso em uma decisão clara, auditável e consumível.\\n\\n### 2) What is already solid\\n- Separação PM = decide **o que**, VO = decide/coordena **como**.\\n- Lógica de runway e priorização já está conceptualmente clara.\\n- Handoff PM -> VO já existe no desenho via job JSON.\\n- Uso de YAML por conta/canal está bem estabelecido nos docs.\\n- Papel do PM dentro da hierarquia nova já está razoavelmente claro no doc principal.\\n\\n### 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\\n- `read_pub` continua não implementado; sem isso o PM não é operacional.\\n- Mirror do PM ainda está preso a nomenclatura antiga (`branches`), o que pode induzir implementação errada.\\n- Não há validador formal do job antes do handoff.\\n- Política de falha está indefinida em casos reais: sheet inconsistente, datas mal formatadas, YAML inconsistente, falha parcial da API.\\n- Fonte de verdade final ainda está ambígua se PUB e YAML divergirem.\\n- Unicidade/idempotência de `job_id` está incerta.\\n\\n### 4) Concrete implementation sequence\\n1. Congelar contrato canónico do job JSON do PM.\\n2. Definir convenção única de naming/checkpoints/paths usados pelo PM.\\n3. Implementar `read_pub` com normalização de datas e colunas.\\n4. Implementar `job_builder` para converter canal escolhido + configs em job JSON.\\n5. Implementar `job_validator` para validar schema, obrigatórios e consistência mínima.\\n6. Testar PM com snapshots reais da PUB e 10+ casos representativos.\\n7. Só depois ligar output do PM ao VO mínimo.\\n\\n### 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\\n**PM supervisor / core logic**\\n- [ ] Lê PUB real\\n- [ ] Normaliza datas/colunas quebradas\\n- [ ] Calcula runway ordenado\\n- [ ] Aplica overrides deterministicamente\\n- [ ] Resolve empate de prioridade\\n- [ ] Escolhe canal final\\n- [ ] Gera `job_id`\\n- [ ] Produz job JSON canónico\\n- [ ] Valida job antes de publicar\\n- [ ] Escreve artefacto e log mínimo\\n\\n**read_pub skill**\\n- [ ] Conecta à Google Sheets API\\n- [ ] Lê colunas necessárias\\n- [ ] Faz parse de `ULT PUB`, `PROGRAMAR`, `PROD`, `SCRIPTS`\\n- [ ] Normaliza formatos inconsistentes\\n- [ ] Retorna estrutura estável\\n\\n**job_builder skill**\\n- [ ] Carrega YAMLs necessários\\n- [ ] Monta payload final\\n- [ ] Injeta paths/checkpoints/schema_version\\n- [ ] Não inventa defaults perigosos\\n\\n**job_validator skill**\\n- [ ] Campos obrigatórios\\n- [ ] Tipos\\n- [ ] Coerência de paths\\n- [ ] IDs válidos\\n- [ ] Erros estruturados\\n\\n### 6) Decisions Lucca must make live\\n- Qual é a fonte de verdade final se PUB e YAML divergirem?\\n- Em falha de leitura da PUB: abortar, usar cache, ou usar último snapshot válido?\\n- `job_id` deve ser timestamp-based, UUID, ou composto por account/lang/date?\\n- Qual critério exacto de desempate quando múltiplos canais empatam?\\n- Quais overrides o Tobias/Lucca podem passar na v1 e qual formato canónico desses overrides?\\n\\n### 7) What Claude Code can implement without waiting\\n- Schema inicial do job JSON.\\n- `job_validator`.\\n- Estrutura/base de `job_builder`.\\n- Normalizador de row da PUB.\\n- Fixture tests com exemplos simulados/reais sanitizados.\\n- Cleanup do mirror do PM para remover linguagem antiga e alinhar naming.\\n\\n### 8) What likely reuses from V3 vs net-new\\n**Provável reuse de V3**\\n- Parte da lógica de priorização/runway, se já existia em scripts/utilitários.\\n- Estruturas de config por conta/canal.\\n- Qualquer wrapper anterior de Sheets, se existir.\\n\\n**Net-new provável**\\n- Contrato formal PM -> VO.\\n- `job_validator`.\\n- Normalização robusta da PUB.\\n- Política de erro/cache/fallback.\\n- Convenção de output/checkpoints alinhada à arquitectura nova.\\n\\n### 9) First 3 concrete implementation tasks\\n1. Criar `pm_job.schema.json` + exemplo canónico de job válido.\\n2. Implementar `read_pub` com normalização e teste em snapshot real/sanitizado.\\n3. Implementar `job_validator` e travar emissão de job inválido.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## VO — Video Orchestrator\\n\\n### 1) Mission of the sector/component\\nO VO existe para transformar um job válido numa execução coordenada da pipeline. Ele inicializa diretórios/estado, faz fetch+lock do script, despacha setores na ordem certa, respeita dependências e paralelismo, consolida status, e fecha a corrida com report final. O VO não deve absorver ambiguidade estrutural dos setores; deve operar sobre contratos já congelados.\\n\\n### 2) What is already solid\\n- Papel do VO como coração da execução está claro.\\n- Sequência macro S1 -> S10 está bem definida.\\n- Dependências principais já estão mapeadas, incluindo S2 + S3 em paralelo.\\n- Responsabilidades de lock/report/cleanup já aparecem no doc.\\n- Separação PM vs VO está madura.\\n\\n### 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\\n- Workspace mirror do VO está ausente.\\n- Contrato de invocação supervisor/setor ainda não está formalizado.\\n- Error policy está vaga demais para automação segura.\\n- Ownership de checkpoints, crash recovery e lock lifecycle continua indefinido.\\n- Sem contracts estáveis, o VO só orquestra drift.\\n- Se implementado cedo demais, cristaliza erros de naming e handoff.\\n\\n### 4) Concrete implementation sequence\\n1. Não começar pelo VO pleno.\\n2. Congelar primeiro contrato mínimo de dispatch/status/error/checkpoint.\\n3. Criar `workspace_mirror/video_orchestrator/` alinhado com a arquitectura actual.\\n4. Implementar `video_dir_initializer`.\\n5. Implementar `script_fetch_and_lock`.\\n6. Implementar `sector_dispatcher` mínimo viável para chamar um setor por vez com input/output canónicos.\\n7. Implementar `checkpoint_resolver`.\\n8. Implementar `final_report_builder`.\\n9. Só depois adicionar retry taxonomy, pause/recovery e paralelismo real.\\n\\n### 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\\n**VO core**\\n- [ ] Recebe job validado\\n- [ ] Valida pré-condições do run\\n- [ ] Inicializa diretório do vídeo\\n- [ ] Obtém script + lock\\n- [ ] Escreve estado inicial\\n- [ ] Despacha setores conforme dependências\\n- [ ] Lê checkpoints/resultados\\n- [ ] Classifica falha vs retry vs escalonamento\\n- [ ] Consolida report final\\n- [ ] Liberta lock e fecha run\\n\\n**video_dir_initializer**\\n- [ ] Cria estrutura mínima de pastas\\n- [ ] Escreve metadata inicial do run\\n- [ ] Não sobrescreve corrida anterior indevidamente\\n\\n**script_fetch_and_lock**\\n- [ ] Busca script certo\\n- [ ] Aplica lock com owner claro\\n- [ ] Detecta lock órfão\\n- [ ] Retorna erro estruturado\\n\\n**sector_dispatcher**\\n- [ ] Input canónico por setor\\n- [ ] Execução mínima reproduzível\\n- [ ] Capta output/checkpoint\\n- [ ] Retorna status estruturado\\n\\n**checkpoint_resolver**\\n- [ ] Encontra último estado válido\\n- [ ] Decide resume vs restart\\n- [ ] Detecta checkpoint incompleto/corrompido\\n\\n**final_report_builder**\\n- [ ] Lista setores completos\\n- [ ] Lista falhas/pendências\\n- [ ] Resume artefactos gerados\\n- [ ] Marca upload/tracking/script release quando aplicável\\n\\n### 6) Decisions Lucca must make live\\n- Qual é o contrato mínimo de status por setor? JSON único, filesystem markers, ou ambos?\\n- Quem é owner do lock do script em crash/recovery?\\n- Em falha de um setor, o VO continua setores independentes ou pausa tudo?\\n- Qual taxonomia canónica de erros da v1?\\n- O VO v1 vai suportar paralelismo real ou apenas sequência + pontos paralelizáveis controlados?\\n\\n### 7) What Claude Code can implement without waiting\\n- Estrutura inicial do mirror do VO.\\n- Schemas de `sector_dispatch_request`, `sector_result`, `run_status`, `structured_error`.\\n- `video_dir_initializer`.\\n- `final_report_builder`.\\n- `checkpoint_resolver` mínimo.\\n- Skeleton de `sector_dispatcher` com interface estável, mesmo que alguns setores ainda sejam stubs.\\n\\n### 8) What likely reuses from V3 vs net-new\\n**Provável reuse de V3**\\n- Parte da lógica de bootstrap de diretório do vídeo.\\n- Possível lógica anterior de lock/fetch de script.\\n- Estruturas de report final/estado de produção, se existirem.\\n\\n**Net-new provável**\\n- Mirror do VO.\\n- Contrato formal entre VO e supervisores.\\n- Taxonomia estruturada de erros/retries.\\n- Recovery/checkpoint ownership alinhado ao sistema novo.\\n\\n### 9) First 3 concrete implementation tasks\\n1. Criar schema de dispatch/status/error/checkpoint do VO.\\n2. Implementar `video_dir_initializer` + `final_report_builder` mínimos.\\n3. Criar mirror do VO e um `sector_dispatcher` stub com interface canónica.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## S1 — Pre-Production\\n\\n### 1) Mission of the sector/component\\nS1 existe para transformar o script bruto num pacote fundador confiável para o resto da pipeline: screenplay preservado, texto polido para TTS sem degradar sentido, e `scene_bible` inicial com direção visual útil. É o setor que fixa a base narrativa/estrutural; se ele errar, os setores seguintes só amplificam erro.\\n\\n### 2) What is already solid\\n- S1 é um dos setores mais fortes conceptualmente.\\n- `scene_director` está bem pensado e com filosofia criativa sólida.\\n- Estrutura supervisor + operadores + skills já está razoavelmente madura no doc.\\n- Ideia de validação determinística + correção cirúrgica está correcta.\\n- `tts_polish` já aparece melhor definido do que antes.\\n\\n### 3) What is ambiguous / dangerous\\n- Validators continuam blockers reais (`screenplay_validator`, `polish_validator`).\\n- Mirror está desalinhado do doc oficial.\\n- Checkpoints divergem (`b1_` vs `s1_`).\\n- Mirror simplifica demais outputs e pode induzir implementação incompleta.\\n- CLI/comandos do mirror parecem pseudo-interface não validada.\\n- Schema do `scene_bible` ainda não está formalizado o suficiente.\\n\\n### 4) Concrete implementation sequence\\n1. Escolher convenção canónica: `s1_` ou `b1_` e congelar.\\n2. Congelar schema mínimo do `scene_bible.json` inicial.\\n3. Implementar `screenplay_validator`.\\n4. Implementar `polish_validator`.\\n5. Reescrever mirror de S1 alinhado ao doc oficial.\\n6. Formalizar feedback loop supervisor <-> operador por cena.\\n7. Testar S1 ponta a ponta com 2-3 scripts reais longos.\\n\\n### 5) Operator-by-operator checklist\\n**SM-S1**\\n- [ ] Carrega script/job/contexto\\n- [ ] Divide fluxo por cenas/segmentos conforme contrato\\n- [ ] Chama operadores na ordem certa\\n- [ ] Usa validators antes de aprovar output\\n- [ ] Faz correção cirúrgica quando falhar\\n- [ ] Escreve checkpoints consistentes\\n- [ ] Escala após limite de falhas\\n\\n**scene_director**\\n- [ ] Mantém fidelidade ao áudio\\n- [ ] Produz `visual_direction` útil e acionável\\n- [ ] Não inventa estrutura fora do script\\n- [ ] Retorna formato canónico por cena\\n\\n**tts_polish**\\n- [ ] Respeita YAML por idioma\\n- [ ] Melhora oralidade sem mudar sentido\\n- [ ] Não apaga informação factual\\n- [ ] Retorna diff/estrutura rastreável quando possível\\n\\n**scene_bible_builder**\\n- [ ] Cria `scene_bible.json` inicial\\n- [ ] Inclui campos reservados para setores futuros\\n- [ ] Mantém schema estável\\n- [ ] Não mistura responsabilidades de setores seguintes\\n\\n**screenplay_validator**\\n- [ ] Confirma preservação do conteúdo narrado\\n- [ ] Detecta omissões/adições indevidas\\n- [ ] Retorna erro específico por cena\\n\\n**polish_validator**\\n- [ ] Confirma que polish não degradou sentido\\n- [ ] Marca alterações perigosas\\n- [ ] Retorna feedback utilizável para retry\\n\\n### 6) Decision\n...(truncated)..."}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":12664,"output":6203,"totalTokens":29747,"cacheRead":10880,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"total":0.127425}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774794499695,"responseId":"resp_0ecb2fb499bb29d00169c93706406481919c563cc9394b59d2","__openclaw":{"id":"f2bf9fab","seq":10}},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Concluído.\n\nCriei o ficheiro:\n- `C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\reviews\\tobias_review_29mar\\23_sector_execution_plan_A.md`\n\nO pack está estruturado para PM, VO, S1, S2 e S3 com os 9 blocos pedidos para cada um:\n- missão\n- sólido\n- ambíguo/perigoso\n- sequência concreta\n- checklist por operador\n- decisões live do Lucca\n- o que Claude Code pode fazer já\n- reuse V3 vs net-new\n- 3 primeiras tasks concretas\n\nPontos relevantes para o requester:\n- Mantive o foco em execução prática, não teoria.\n- Usei apenas o material das reviews/docs indicadas.\n- Forcei a lógica de **contract freeze primeiro**, porque isso aparece como risco estrutural recorrente em quase todos os componentes.\n- Em S2 deixei explícito que a primeira decisão é matar a bifurcação doc vs mirror antes de implementação séria.\n- No VO deixei claro que o caminho correcto é **VO mínimo depois dos contratos core**, não VO pleno cedo.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0ecb2fb499bb29d00169c93779bcb88191924618207287355d\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":228,"output":242,"totalTokens":30038,"cacheRead":29568,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"total":0.011591999999999998}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774794614972,"responseId":"resp_0ecb2fb499bb29d00169c93778b9c08191ad0aea7da9ad8147","__openclaw":{"id":"5c62b302","seq":12}}]},{"key":"agent:main:subagent:bce133f4-39ae-4582-9c63-4ec2d5c0522e","kind":"other","channel":"webchat","spawnedBy":"agent:main:main","label":"claude-code-backlog","displayName":"webchat:g-agent-main-subagent-bce133f4-39ae-4582-9c63-4ec2d5c0522e","parentSessionKey":"agent:main:main","deliveryContext":{"channel":"webchat"},"updatedAt":1774794617356,"sessionId":"9fe9792b-f890-45be-98d5-5f47b76e6e70","model":"gpt-5.4","contextTokens":272000,"totalTokens":50286,"estimatedCostUsd":0.2521385,"status":"done","startedAt":1774794446810,"endedAt":1774794608647,"runtimeMs":160541,"abortedLastRun":false,"lastChannel":"webchat","transcriptPath":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\main\\sessions\\9fe9792b-f890-45be-98d5-5f47b76e6e70.jsonl","messages":[{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Planning file writing**\n\nI need to write a file, possibly reviewing sectors like S9 and S2 for clarity. It might be helpful to check headings too. I believe I should outline specific files or modules to address, particularly in docs and workspace_mirror. It’s a good idea to suggest new code directories, even if they don’t exist yet, like src/ or skills/. I should consider practical implementation for Claude Code and define new module paths, but I’ll try not to overcomplicate things. I plan to create a backlog that includes suggested directories and a deterministic layer since the codebase is lacking. I'll aim for something concise but meaningful, organized into six phases."},{"type":"text","text":"Vou escrever o backlog final como um plano de implementação orientado a Claude Code, já traduzindo a auditoria em bundles de engenharia e apontando os pontos do repo que provavelmente terão de ser tocados primeiro.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_043858592f200ba20169c936efe4d88191b77d44b2b5d24f18\",\"phase\":\"commentary\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_HRmkfjZcI6iijQAMidhaBI2k|fc_043858592f200ba20169c936eff7448191a05f107857766ed7","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\reviews\\tobias_review_29mar\\26_claude_code_task_backlog.md","content":"# Claude Code Implementation Task Backlog — 29 Mar 2026\n\n## Purpose\nThis backlog translates the Tobias audit into a practical implementation sequence for Claude Code.\n\nPrinciples used:\n- prioritize contract stability before broad implementation\n- bundle work into meaningful engineering slices, not tiny tickets\n- bias toward deterministic substrate, validators, wrappers, and handoff reliability\n- defer full orchestration until sector contracts are stable\n\n---\n\n# Phase 0 — Contract freeze and repo alignment\n\n## Task 0.1 — Freeze canonical naming, artefact, and checkpoint conventions\n- **Why it matters:** The biggest system risk is contract drift. Claude Code should not implement against ambiguous naming such as `b#_` vs `s#_`, `scene_id` vs `moment_id`, or mixed checkpoint/file conventions.\n- **Dependencies:** None.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `docs/04_BRANCH_ARCHITECTURE.md`\n  - `docs/09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md`\n  - `docs/12_VIDEO_DIRECTORY_STRUCTURE.md`\n  - `docs/03_PIPELINE_MAP.md`\n  - `docs/branches/01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md`\n  - `docs/branches/02_AUDIO.md`\n  - `docs/branches/05_VISUAL_DIRECTION.md`\n  - `docs/branches/07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md`\n  - `docs/branches/08_POST_PRODUCTION.md`\n  - `docs/branches/09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - one canonical naming convention is explicitly documented\n  - one checkpoint naming/path convention is explicitly documented\n  - one artefact naming convention exists for JSON, manifests, and TSX outputs\n  - handoff terminology is consistent across core docs\n- **Priority:** P0\n\n## Task 0.2 — Run a workspace mirror cleanup sprint\n- **Why it matters:** The mirror currently contains old terminology and intermediate specs that can mislead implementation. Claude Code needs the mirror to reflect the chosen canonical version or be clearly marked as legacy.\n- **Dependencies:** Task 0.1.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `workspace_mirror/production_manager/**`\n  - `workspace_mirror/branches/**`\n  - especially legacy `agents/` paths under each sector mirror\n  - possibly a new repo note such as `docs/00_CONTEXT.md` or a dedicated alignment note\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - each mirror area is either aligned to the current spec or explicitly marked legacy\n  - obvious branch/agent naming drift is removed or annotated\n  - sector mirror prompts/rules do not contradict the canonical docs on inputs/outputs\n- **Priority:** P0\n\n## Task 0.3 — Define formal handoff schemas for critical artefacts\n- **Why it matters:** The reviews repeatedly identify missing formal contracts as the main blocker. This task creates the implementation substrate Claude Code can code against safely.\n- **Dependencies:** Task 0.1.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - new schema area, e.g. `schemas/`\n  - likely schema files for `job`, `scene_bible`, `checkpoints`, `asset_json`, `visual_brief`, `image_generation_manifest`, `s7_planner_outputs`, `s8_planner_outputs`, `production_report`\n  - related references in `docs/branches/*.md`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - JSON Schema files exist for the critical handoffs\n  - each schema declares required fields, IDs, timing units, and ownership assumptions\n  - docs point to the schema files as the source of truth\n- **Priority:** P0\n\n---\n\n# Phase 1 — Shared deterministic substrate\n\n## Task 1.1 — Create the core runtime skeleton for shared deterministic infrastructure\n- **Why it matters:** The system needs a real substrate layer for validators, path helpers, locks, schema loading, and structured results. Without this, sector implementation will duplicate logic and drift again.\n- **Dependencies:** Phase 0 complete or materially stable.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - new code area such as `src/` or `runtime/`\n  - likely shared packages/modules for:\n    - `contracts/`\n    - `schemas/loader`\n    - `io/atomic_write`\n    - `io/paths`\n    - `locks/`\n    - `checkpoints/`\n    - `errors/`\n    - `results/`\n  - `README.md`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - repo has a clear shared runtime structure for deterministic helpers\n  - shared path resolution, atomic JSON write, schema loading, and error/result primitives exist\n  - sector code can import shared helpers rather than hardcoding conventions\n- **Priority:** P0\n\n## Task 1.2 — Implement scene_bible I/O, locking, merge, and version semantics\n- **Why it matters:** `scene_bible` is becoming the central system artefact from S2 through S9. If this contract is weak, downstream implementation will become fragile fast.\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 0.3 and 1.1.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - new shared modules such as:\n    - `runtime/scene_bible/read_write.py`\n    - `runtime/scene_bible/lock_manager.py`\n    - `runtime/scene_bible/merge.py`\n    - `runtime/scene_bible/versioning.py`\n  - `docs/branches/01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md`\n  - `docs/branches/02_AUDIO.md`\n  - `docs/branches/03_VISUAL_PLANNING.md`\n  - `docs/branches/05_VISUAL_DIRECTION.md`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - canonical read/lock/update/write flow exists\n  - concurrent writes are prevented or explicitly rejected\n  - partial sector updates can be merged without corrupting unrelated sections\n  - scene_bible version/check metadata is written consistently\n- **Priority:** P0\n\n## Task 1.3 — Implement checkpoint contract and recovery primitives\n- **Why it matters:** Resume/retry/recovery semantics are required by VO, PM, and every later sector. The audit explicitly flags checkpoint ambiguity as a systemic risk.\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 0.1, 0.3, and 1.1.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - new shared modules such as:\n    - `runtime/checkpoints/writer.py`\n    - `runtime/checkpoints/validator.py`\n    - `runtime/checkpoints/resolver.py`\n    - `runtime/checkpoints/models.py`\n  - `docs/12_VIDEO_DIRECTORY_STRUCTURE.md`\n  - `docs/11_VIDEO_ORCHESTRATOR.md`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - canonical checkpoint format exists\n  - each checkpoint includes sector, status, timestamps, and recovery metadata\n  - recovery logic can identify last valid step and next executable step\n  - corrupted/missing checkpoint cases are handled explicitly\n- **Priority:** P0\n\n## Task 1.4 — Build shared schema validation and structured error classification\n- **Why it matters:** Many P0 skills in the audit are validators. They should not be scattered one by one before a common validation/error framework exists.\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 0.3 and 1.1.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `runtime/validation/`\n  - `runtime/errors/`\n  - `runtime/contracts/`\n  - likely common validators for job, scene_bible, assets, visual brief, planner outputs\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - schema-first validation helpers exist\n  - validation failures return structured, machine-usable errors\n  - errors are classifiable as retryable, fatal, or operator-action-needed\n- **Priority:** P0\n\n---\n\n# Phase 2 — PM core and external wrappers\n\n## Task 2.1 — Implement Production Manager ingestion and job-building core\n- **Why it matters:** PM is the front door of the pipeline. Claude Code needs a stable way to read the publication source, normalize rows, build jobs, and validate them before sector execution starts.\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 1.1, 1.3, and 1.4.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `docs/10_PRODUCTION_MANAGER.md`\n  - `workspace_mirror/production_manager/**`\n  - new modules such as:\n    - `runtime/pm/read_pub.py`\n    - `runtime/pm/pub_row_normalizer.py`\n    - `runtime/pm/job_builder.py`\n    - `runtime/pm/job_validator.py`\n    - `runtime/pm/override_parser.py`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - publication source can be read into normalized records\n  - a canonical job artefact is produced\n  - invalid jobs are rejected with clear validation output\n  - output pathing follows the Phase 0 conventions\n- **Priority:** P0\n\n## Task 2.2 — Implement video directory initialization and filesystem scaffolding\n- **Why it matters:** The whole pipeline depends on predictable per-video structure. This should be deterministic and created once, not improvised by sectors later.\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 0.1, 1.1, and 2.1.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `docs/12_VIDEO_DIRECTORY_STRUCTURE.md`\n  - new modules such as:\n    - `runtime/pm/video_dir_initializer.py`\n    - `runtime/io/video_paths.py`\n  - any sample output definitions referenced in docs\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - a new job can materialize the canonical directory tree\n  - expected folders for artefacts, checkpoints, renders, reports, and sector outputs are created deterministically\n  - reruns are idempotent and do not corrupt prior state\n- **Priority:** P0\n\n## Task 2.3 — Build the first wrapper set: Sheets, TTS, and transcription/alignment\n- **Why it matters:** These are the first external dependencies that unblock real pipeline value. The audit identifies their contracts as critical missing tooling surfaces.\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 1.1 and 1.4.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - new wrapper modules such as:\n    - `runtime/integrations/google_sheets.py`\n    - `runtime/integrations/gemini_tts.py`\n    - `runtime/integrations/whisperx.py`\n  - `docs/10_PRODUCTION_MANAGER.md`\n  - `docs/branches/02_AUDIO.md`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - wrapper input/output contracts are explicit and stable\n  - retries and failure modes are normalized\n  - produced files and metadata follow canonical naming/output locations\n  - wrapper results can be consumed downstream without adapter glue in sector code\n- **Priority:** P0\n\n---\n\n# Phase 3 — First production-capable chain: S1, S2, S4\n\n## Task 3.1 — Implement S1 validators and canonical output writers\n- **Why it matters:** S1 is one of the strongest sectors conceptually and is the best early place to start real production implementation. Its outputs become the foundation for downstream work.\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 1.2, 1.3, 1.4, and 2.2.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `docs/branches/01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md`\n  - `workspace_mirror/branches/01_pre_production/**`\n  - new modules such as:\n    - `runtime/s1/screenplay_validator.py`\n    - `runtime/s1/polish_validator.py`\n    - `runtime/s1/scene_bible_schema_validator.py`\n    - `runtime/s1/checkpoint_writer.py`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - S1 outputs can be validated deterministically\n  - initial scene_bible artefact can be written in canonical form\n  - S1 emits valid checkpoints and failure diagnostics\n- **Priority:** P0\n\n## Task 3.2 — Unify and implement S2 audio generation, transcription, timestamp alignment, and bible updates\n- **Why it matters:** S2 is strategically important because it introduces real timing. But the audit explicitly says S2 is split across competing versions, so Claude Code should fix the contract while implementing it.\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 0.1, 0.3, 1.2, and 2.3.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `docs/branches/02_AUDIO.md`\n  - `workspace_mirror/branches/02_audio/**`\n  - new modules such as:\n    - `runtime/s2/tts_generator.py`\n    - `runtime/s2/audio_transcriber.py`\n    - `runtime/s2/timestamp_aligner.py`\n    - `runtime/s2/bible_updater.py`\n    - `runtime/s2/alignment_confidence_checker.py`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - there is one canonical S2 flow documented and implemented\n  - TTS audio, alignment output, and timing artefacts are written predictably\n  - scene_bible is updated with temporal data via the shared I/O layer\n  - confidence/failure cases are surfaced for retry/escalation\n- **Priority:** P0\n\n## Task 3.3 — Implement S4 asset ingestion, validation, dedupe, and indexing core\n- **Why it matters:** S4 is mature enough to implement early and creates reusable assets that strengthen S5 and S6 instead of leaving them to operate on weak upstream data.\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 0.3, 1.4, and 2.2.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `docs/branches/04_ASSET_RESEARCH.md`\n  - `workspace_mirror/branches/04_asset_research/**`\n  - new modules such as:\n    - `runtime/s4/asset_json_schema_validator.py`\n    - `runtime/s4/asset_deduplicator.py`\n    - `runtime/s4/asset_license_validator.py`\n    - `runtime/s4/asset_path_materializer.py`\n    - `runtime/s4/asset_index_builder.py`\n    - `runtime/s4/asset_quality_filter.py`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - asset records are schema-valid and stored consistently\n  - duplicate/low-quality/unlicensed assets are filtered or flagged\n  - sector output includes a usable consolidated asset index for S5\n- **Priority:** P0\n\n---\n\n# Phase 4 — Visual intelligence layer: S3 hardening, S5, S6\n\n## Task 4.1 — Harden S3 with validation, dedupe, and searchability scoring\n- **Why it matters:** S3 is useful but currently too soft to serve as reliable substrate for S4/S5. Hardening it now prevents low-quality identifiers from polluting the whole visual chain.\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 1.2, 1.4, and 3.3.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `docs/branches/03_VISUAL_PLANNING.md`\n  - `workspace_mirror/branches/03_visual_planning/**`\n  - new modules such as:\n    - `runtime/s3/entity_output_validator.py`\n    - `runtime/s3/entity_deduplicator.py`\n    - `runtime/s3/searchability_scorer.py`\n    - `runtime/s3/cross_identifier_consistency_checker.py`\n    - `runtime/s3/bible_updater.py`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - S3 outputs are validated and normalized before downstream use\n  - duplicate or weak identifiers are collapsed or downgraded\n  - searchability is scored in a way S4 can actually use\n- **Priority:** P1\n\n## Task 4.2 — Implement S5 narrative blocks, asset matching, and compiled visual brief generation\n- **Why it matters:** S5 is the main architectural innovation in the audit. It is the bridge that turns narrative plus assets into coherent visual direction rather than isolated prompts.\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 3.3 and 4.1.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `docs/branches/05_VISUAL_DIRECTION.md`\n  - `workspace_mirror/branches/05_visual_direction/**`\n  - new modules such as:\n    - `runtime/s5/narrative_block_validator.py`\n    - `runtime/s5/asset_match_schema_validator.py`\n    - `runtime/s5/visual_brief_schema_validator.py`\n    - `runtime/s5/running_summary_manager.py`\n    - `runtime/s5/compiled_visual_brief_builder.py`\n    - `runtime/s5/keep_previous_resolver.py`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - S5 can produce canonical narrative blocks and asset matches\n  - running summary and continuity state are explicitly persisted\n  - compiled visual brief is usable as direct input for S6 and S7\n- **Priority:** P1\n\n## Task 4.3 — Implement S6 prompt building, browser generation execution, portrait consistency, and output manifesting\n- **Why it matters:** S6 should not be a vague intelligent layer. It should be a deterministic executor of S5 decisions, with strong retries and output normalization.\n- **Dependencies:** Task 4.2 plus stable image-generation provider assumptions.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `docs/branches/06_IMAGE_GENERATION.md`\n  - `workspace_mirror/branches/06_image_generation/**`\n  - new modules such as:\n    - `runtime/s6/prompt_builder.py`\n    - `runtime/s6/browser_generation_runner.py`\n    - `runtime/s6/portrait_manager.py`\n    - `runtime/s6/image_generation_manifest_validator.py`\n    - `runtime/s6/image_retry_router.py`\n    - `runtime/s6/image_output_normalizer.py`\n    - `runtime/s6/image_qa_resolver.py`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - S6 consumes the compiled visual brief without ad hoc transformation\n  - generation outputs are harvested into a canonical manifest\n  - retry routing is explicit by provider/model/variation reason\n  - portrait/character continuity is preserved or flagged when broken\n- **Priority:** P1\n\n---\n\n# Phase 5 — Remotion production layer: S7 and S8\n\n## Task 5.1 — Implement S7 planner validators and TSX builders for animation, transitions, composition, and VFX\n- **Why it matters:** S7 is where the system starts materializing renderable scene components. The audit says the architecture is strong; the main need is to freeze builder inputs and output naming.\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 0.3, 4.2, and partially 4.3 if generated imagery is required in tests.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `docs/branches/07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md`\n  - `workspace_mirror/branches/07_scene_composition/**`\n  - new modules such as:\n    - `runtime/s7/planner_output_validator.py`\n    - `runtime/s7/animation_tsx_builder.py`\n    - `runtime/s7/transition_tsx_builder.py`\n    - `runtime/s7/composition_tsx_builder.py`\n    - `runtime/s7/vfx_tsx_builder.py`\n    - `runtime/s7/composition_catalog_validator.py`\n  - likely a new TSX output tree such as `remotion/components/` or equivalent\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - planner outputs validate against canonical schemas\n  - TSX files are generated with stable names/locations\n  - generated components are structurally consistent with the chosen Remotion project layout\n- **Priority:** P1\n\n## Task 5.2 — Implement S8 audio resolving and TSX builders for music, SFX, and lettering\n- **Why it matters:** S8 looks simpler than it is. If lettering ownership and audio resolution are fuzzy here, S9 becomes a cleanup dump. This task should keep S8 deterministic and narrow.\n- **Dependencies:** Task 5.1 and stable S2 timing outputs.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `docs/branches/08_POST_PRODUCTION.md`\n  - `workspace_mirror/branches/08_post_production/**`\n  - new modules such as:\n    - `runtime/s8/audio_resolver.py`\n    - `runtime/s8/music_tsx_builder.py`\n    - `runtime/s8/sfx_tsx_builder.py`\n    - `runtime/s8/lettering_tsx_builder.py`\n    - `runtime/s8/lettering_content_validator.py`\n    - `runtime/s8/lettering_style_resolver.py`\n    - `runtime/s8/planner_output_validator.py`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - audio/music/SFX/lettering inputs resolve to canonical media references\n  - TSX output is stable and merge-ready for S9\n  - lettering content vs visual style responsibilities are separated cleanly\n- **Priority:** P1\n\n---\n\n# Phase 6 — Review, render, and delivery\n\n## Task 6.1 — Resolve S9 contract contradictions and implement review gates before render\n- **Why it matters:** S9 is the most contradictory part of the system. Claude Code should not jump to render orchestration until reviewer set, component naming, resolution, and merge gates are made explicit.\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 5.1 and 5.2.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `docs/branches/09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md`\n  - `workspace_mirror/branches/09_assembly_render/**`\n  - new modules such as:\n    - `runtime/s9/tsx_component_diff_checker.py`\n    - `runtime/s9/merge_gate_validator.py`\n    - `runtime/s9/overlap_detector.py`\n    - `runtime/s9/audio_sync_checker.py`\n    - `runtime/s9/audio_levels_checker.py`\n    - `runtime/s9/review_packet_builder.py`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - S9 has one canonical reviewer/gate model\n  - pre-render validation catches structural TSX mismatches, overlaps, sync, and audio-level issues\n  - S9 no longer depends on undocumented reviewer assumptions\n- **Priority:** P0\n\n## Task 6.2 — Implement render execution and context-aware fix loop\n- **Why it matters:** Once review gates are stable, render becomes the deterministic execution step. The fix loop must be explicit so failures do not devolve into manual chaos.\n- **Dependencies:** Task 6.1.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `docs/branches/09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md`\n  - new modules such as:\n    - `runtime/s9/render_command_runner.py`\n    - `runtime/s9/render_output_validator.py`\n    - `runtime/s9/render_fix_executor.py`\n  - likely Remotion project files/output configuration\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - canonical render command can be invoked deterministically\n  - render output success/failure is validated automatically\n  - known failure classes can trigger structured fixes or escalation\n- **Priority:** P1\n\n## Task 6.3 — Implement S10 finalization, idempotent delivery, and production reporting\n- **Why it matters:** S10 is conceptually simple, but it closes the factory. Without idempotent finalization, duplicate uploads and broken status reporting will create operational noise fast.\n- **Dependencies:** Task 6.2 and external destination assumptions.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `docs/branches/10_FINALIZATION.md`\n  - `workspace_mirror/branches/10_finalization/**`\n  - new modules such as:\n    - `runtime/s10/compressor.py`\n    - `runtime/s10/metadata_stripper.py`\n    - `runtime/s10/drive_uploader.py`\n    - `runtime/s10/sheets_updater.py`\n    - `runtime/s10/release_script_lock.py`\n    - `runtime/s10/production_reporter.py`\n    - `runtime/s10/idempotency_guard.py`\n    - `runtime/s10/delivery_artifact_validator.py`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - final video package can be compressed, cleaned, uploaded, and reported exactly once\n  - locks are released safely on success/failure paths\n  - final production report is written in canonical format\n- **Priority:** P0\n\n---\n\n# Phase 7 — Video Orchestrator and end-to-end automation\n\n## Task 7.1 — Implement minimal VO execution loop on top of stable sectors\n- **Why it matters:** The audit is clear: VO should come after the contracts and sectors. At this point Claude Code can implement a thin but real orchestrator instead of an elegant abstraction over ambiguity.\n- **Dependencies:** Phases 1 through 6 materially complete.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `docs/11_VIDEO_ORCHESTRATOR.md`\n  - `workspace_mirror/tobias/**` if operational interactions are mirrored there\n  - new modules such as:\n    - `runtime/vo/script_fetch_and_lock.py`\n    - `runtime/vo/sector_dispatcher.py`\n    - `runtime/vo/checkpoint_resolver.py`\n    - `runtime/vo/status_aggregator.py`\n    - `runtime/vo/final_report_builder.py`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - VO can fetch a job, initialize execution, dispatch sectors, and resume from checkpoints\n  - cross-sector state is aggregated into a job-level status model\n  - final report is assembled from sector outputs rather than manual stitching\n- **Priority:** P1\n\n## Task 7.2 — Add retry, recovery, lock repair, and escalation semantics to VO\n- **Why it matters:** This is the step that turns orchestration into factory-grade operation. It should only be built once sector failure modes are known from real execution.\n- **Dependencies:** Task 7.1 and observed failures from end-to-end runs.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `runtime/vo/retry_classifier.py`\n  - `runtime/vo/lock_recovery_manager.py`\n  - `runtime/errors/`\n  - `runtime/checkpoints/`\n  - `docs/11_VIDEO_ORCHESTRATOR.md`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - retryable vs fatal vs operator-escalation failures are classified consistently\n  - orphaned/broken locks can be repaired safely\n  - recovery paths are based on checkpoint state, not ad hoc heuristics\n- **Priority:** P1\n\n---\n\n# Cross-cutting backlog items\n\n## Task X.1 — Add golden test fixtures for each major handoff\n- **Why it matters:** Contract freeze is not durable without test fixtures. Claude Code should be able to run validators and builders against representative job samples.\n- **Dependencies:** Phase 0 schemas and early runtime structure.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - new test area such as `tests/fixtures/`\n  - fixture sets for `job`, `scene_bible`, `assets`, `visual_brief`, `s7 planner outputs`, `s8 planner outputs`, `production_report`\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - each critical schema has at least one valid fixture and key invalid fixtures\n  - validators/builders can be regression-tested against stable examples\n- **Priority:** P0\n\n## Task X.2 — Add end-to-end smoke pipeline with one narrow account/video profile\n- **Why it matters:** The system should be proven on one constrained path before broadening across accounts, styles, and languages.\n- **Dependencies:** S1, S2, S4, and minimal downstream execution readiness.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `accounts/*.yaml`\n  - new smoke-test runner module or script\n  - PM/VO runtime entrypoints\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - one bounded scenario can run through the implemented chain repeatedly\n  - failures are attributable to specific sector contracts rather than environmental ambiguity\n- **Priority:** P1\n\n## Task X.3 — Add structured observability and per-sector execution reports\n- **Why it matters:** Once Claude Code starts wiring execution together, debugging time will dominate unless logs, statuses, and artefact pointers are standardized.\n- **Dependencies:** Shared runtime and initial sector execution.\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\n  - `runtime/logging/`\n  - `runtime/reports/`\n  - PM/VO and sector runners\n- **Done criteria:**\n  - each sector writes structured execution metadata\n  - job-level reports link to checkpoints, produced artefacts, retries, and failure causes\n  - logs are usable for recovery and review, not just raw stdout\n- **Priority:** P1\n\n---\n\n# Recommended implementation order for Claude Code\n\n## Immediate P0 sequence\n1. Task 0.1 — Freeze canonical naming and artefact conventions\n2. Task 0.2 — Mirror cleanup sprint\n3. Task 0.3 — Formal handoff schemas\n4. Task 1.1 — Shared runtime skeleton\n5. Task 1.2 — `scene_bible` I/O and locking\n6. Task 1.3 — Checkpoint contract\n7. Task 1.4 — Validation and structured errors\n8. Task 2.1 — PM ingestion and job builder\n9. Task 2.2 — Video directory initializer\n10. Task 2.3 — Sheets/TTS/WhisperX wrappers\n11. Task 3.1 — S1 validators and output writers\n12. Task 3.2 — S2 unified implementation\n13. Task 3.3 — S4 asset core\n14. Task X.1 — Golden fixtures\n15. Task 6.1 — S9 contract resolution before heavy render work\n16. Task 6.3 — S10 finalization once render outputs are stable\n\n## Next P1 wave\n17. Task 4.1 — S3 hardening\n18. Task 4.2 — S5\n19. Task 4.3 — S6\n20. Task 5.1 — S7\n21. Task 5.2 — S8\n22. Task 6.2 — Render execution and fix loop\n23. Task 7.1 — Minimal VO\n24. Task 7.2 — Recovery and retry semantics\n25. Task X.2 — E2E smoke pipeline\n26. Task X.3 — Observability\n\n---\n\n# Final guidance for Claude Code\n\nIf there is pressure to start coding immediately, the safest acceleration path is:\n- implement schemas + shared runtime first\n- then PM/S1/S2/S4\n- only then move into S5/S6/S7/S8\n- do not implement full VO early\n- do not treat S9 as a normal downstream sector until its contracts are explicitly cleaned up\n\nThe core rule is simple:\n**build contracts first, then builders, then orchestration.**\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\reviews\\\\tobias_review_29mar\\\\26_claude_code_task_backlog.md\",\"content\":\"# Claude Code Implementation Task Backlog — 29 Mar 2026\\n\\n## Purpose\\nThis backlog translates the Tobias audit into a practical implementation sequence for Claude Code.\\n\\nPrinciples used:\\n- prioritize contract stability before broad implementation\\n- bundle work into meaningful engineering slices, not tiny tickets\\n- bias toward deterministic substrate, validators, wrappers, and handoff reliability\\n- defer full orchestration until sector contracts are stable\\n\\n---\\n\\n# Phase 0 — Contract freeze and repo alignment\\n\\n## Task 0.1 — Freeze canonical naming, artefact, and checkpoint conventions\\n- **Why it matters:** The biggest system risk is contract drift. Claude Code should not implement against ambiguous naming such as `b#_` vs `s#_`, `scene_id` vs `moment_id`, or mixed checkpoint/file conventions.\\n- **Dependencies:** None.\\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\\n  - `docs/04_BRANCH_ARCHITECTURE.md`\\n  - `docs/09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md`\\n  - `docs/12_VIDEO_DIRECTORY_STRUCTURE.md`\\n  - `docs/03_PIPELINE_MAP.md`\\n  - `docs/branches/01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md`\\n  - `docs/branches/02_AUDIO.md`\\n  - `docs/branches/05_VISUAL_DIRECTION.md`\\n  - `docs/branches/07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md`\\n  - `docs/branches/08_POST_PRODUCTION.md`\\n  - `docs/branches/09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md`\\n- **Done criteria:**\\n  - one canonical naming convention is explicitly documented\\n  - one checkpoint naming/path convention is explicitly documented\\n  - one artefact naming convention exists for JSON, manifests, and TSX outputs\\n  - handoff terminology is consistent across core docs\\n- **Priority:** P0\\n\\n## Task 0.2 — Run a workspace mirror cleanup sprint\\n- **Why it matters:** The mirror currently contains old terminology and intermediate specs that can mislead implementation. Claude Code needs the mirror to reflect the chosen canonical version or be clearly marked as legacy.\\n- **Dependencies:** Task 0.1.\\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\\n  - `workspace_mirror/production_manager/**`\\n  - `workspace_mirror/branches/**`\\n  - especially legacy `agents/` paths under each sector mirror\\n  - possibly a new repo note such as `docs/00_CONTEXT.md` or a dedicated alignment note\\n- **Done criteria:**\\n  - each mirror area is either aligned to the current spec or explicitly marked legacy\\n  - obvious branch/agent naming drift is removed or annotated\\n  - sector mirror prompts/rules do not contradict the canonical docs on inputs/outputs\\n- **Priority:** P0\\n\\n## Task 0.3 — Define formal handoff schemas for critical artefacts\\n- **Why it matters:** The reviews repeatedly identify missing formal contracts as the main blocker. This task creates the implementation substrate Claude Code can code against safely.\\n- **Dependencies:** Task 0.1.\\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\\n  - new schema area, e.g. `schemas/`\\n  - likely schema files for `job`, `scene_bible`, `checkpoints`, `asset_json`, `visual_brief`, `image_generation_manifest`, `s7_planner_outputs`, `s8_planner_outputs`, `production_report`\\n  - related references in `docs/branches/*.md`\\n- **Done criteria:**\\n  - JSON Schema files exist for the critical handoffs\\n  - each schema declares required fields, IDs, timing units, and ownership assumptions\\n  - docs point to the schema files as the source of truth\\n- **Priority:** P0\\n\\n---\\n\\n# Phase 1 — Shared deterministic substrate\\n\\n## Task 1.1 — Create the core runtime skeleton for shared deterministic infrastructure\\n- **Why it matters:** The system needs a real substrate layer for validators, path helpers, locks, schema loading, and structured results. Without this, sector implementation will duplicate logic and drift again.\\n- **Dependencies:** Phase 0 complete or materially stable.\\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\\n  - new code area such as `src/` or `runtime/`\\n  - likely shared packages/modules for:\\n    - `contracts/`\\n    - `schemas/loader`\\n    - `io/atomic_write`\\n    - `io/paths`\\n    - `locks/`\\n    - `checkpoints/`\\n    - `errors/`\\n    - `results/`\\n  - `README.md`\\n- **Done criteria:**\\n  - repo has a clear shared runtime structure for deterministic helpers\\n  - shared path resolution, atomic JSON write, schema loading, and error/result primitives exist\\n  - sector code can import shared helpers rather than hardcoding conventions\\n- **Priority:** P0\\n\\n## Task 1.2 — Implement scene_bible I/O, locking, merge, and version semantics\\n- **Why it matters:** `scene_bible` is becoming the central system artefact from S2 through S9. If this contract is weak, downstream implementation will become fragile fast.\\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 0.3 and 1.1.\\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\\n  - new shared modules such as:\\n    - `runtime/scene_bible/read_write.py`\\n    - `runtime/scene_bible/lock_manager.py`\\n    - `runtime/scene_bible/merge.py`\\n    - `runtime/scene_bible/versioning.py`\\n  - `docs/branches/01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md`\\n  - `docs/branches/02_AUDIO.md`\\n  - `docs/branches/03_VISUAL_PLANNING.md`\\n  - `docs/branches/05_VISUAL_DIRECTION.md`\\n- **Done criteria:**\\n  - canonical read/lock/update/write flow exists\\n  - concurrent writes are prevented or explicitly rejected\\n  - partial sector updates can be merged without corrupting unrelated sections\\n  - scene_bible version/check metadata is written consistently\\n- **Priority:** P0\\n\\n## Task 1.3 — Implement checkpoint contract and recovery primitives\\n- **Why it matters:** Resume/retry/recovery semantics are required by VO, PM, and every later sector. The audit explicitly flags checkpoint ambiguity as a systemic risk.\\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 0.1, 0.3, and 1.1.\\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\\n  - new shared modules such as:\\n    - `runtime/checkpoints/writer.py`\\n    - `runtime/checkpoints/validator.py`\\n    - `runtime/checkpoints/resolver.py`\\n    - `runtime/checkpoints/models.py`\\n  - `docs/12_VIDEO_DIRECTORY_STRUCTURE.md`\\n  - `docs/11_VIDEO_ORCHESTRATOR.md`\\n- **Done criteria:**\\n  - canonical checkpoint format exists\\n  - each checkpoint includes sector, status, timestamps, and recovery metadata\\n  - recovery logic can identify last valid step and next executable step\\n  - corrupted/missing checkpoint cases are handled explicitly\\n- **Priority:** P0\\n\\n## Task 1.4 — Build shared schema validation and structured error classification\\n- **Why it matters:** Many P0 skills in the audit are validators. They should not be scattered one by one before a common validation/error framework exists.\\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 0.3 and 1.1.\\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\\n  - `runtime/validation/`\\n  - `runtime/errors/`\\n  - `runtime/contracts/`\\n  - likely common validators for job, scene_bible, assets, visual brief, planner outputs\\n- **Done criteria:**\\n  - schema-first validation helpers exist\\n  - validation failures return structured, machine-usable errors\\n  - errors are classifiable as retryable, fatal, or operator-action-needed\\n- **Priority:** P0\\n\\n---\\n\\n# Phase 2 — PM core and external wrappers\\n\\n## Task 2.1 — Implement Production Manager ingestion and job-building core\\n- **Why it matters:** PM is the front door of the pipeline. Claude Code needs a stable way to read the publication source, normalize rows, build jobs, and validate them before sector execution starts.\\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 1.1, 1.3, and 1.4.\\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\\n  - `docs/10_PRODUCTION_MANAGER.md`\\n  - `workspace_mirror/production_manager/**`\\n  - new modules such as:\\n    - `runtime/pm/read_pub.py`\\n    - `runtime/pm/pub_row_normalizer.py`\\n    - `runtime/pm/job_builder.py`\\n    - `runtime/pm/job_validator.py`\\n    - `runtime/pm/override_parser.py`\\n- **Done criteria:**\\n  - publication source can be read into normalized records\\n  - a canonical job artefact is produced\\n  - invalid jobs are rejected with clear validation output\\n  - output pathing follows the Phase 0 conventions\\n- **Priority:** P0\\n\\n## Task 2.2 — Implement video directory initialization and filesystem scaffolding\\n- **Why it matters:** The whole pipeline depends on predictable per-video structure. This should be deterministic and created once, not improvised by sectors later.\\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 0.1, 1.1, and 2.1.\\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\\n  - `docs/12_VIDEO_DIRECTORY_STRUCTURE.md`\\n  - new modules such as:\\n    - `runtime/pm/video_dir_initializer.py`\\n    - `runtime/io/video_paths.py`\\n  - any sample output definitions referenced in docs\\n- **Done criteria:**\\n  - a new job can materialize the canonical directory tree\\n  - expected folders for artefacts, checkpoints, renders, reports, and sector outputs are created deterministically\\n  - reruns are idempotent and do not corrupt prior state\\n- **Priority:** P0\\n\\n## Task 2.3 — Build the first wrapper set: Sheets, TTS, and transcription/alignment\\n- **Why it matters:** These are the first external dependencies that unblock real pipeline value. The audit identifies their contracts as critical missing tooling surfaces.\\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 1.1 and 1.4.\\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\\n  - new wrapper modules such as:\\n    - `runtime/integrations/google_sheets.py`\\n    - `runtime/integrations/gemini_tts.py`\\n    - `runtime/integrations/whisperx.py`\\n  - `docs/10_PRODUCTION_MANAGER.md`\\n  - `docs/branches/02_AUDIO.md`\\n- **Done criteria:**\\n  - wrapper input/output contracts are explicit and stable\\n  - retries and failure modes are normalized\\n  - produced files and metadata follow canonical naming/output locations\\n  - wrapper results can be consumed downstream without adapter glue in sector code\\n- **Priority:** P0\\n\\n---\\n\\n# Phase 3 — First production-capable chain: S1, S2, S4\\n\\n## Task 3.1 — Implement S1 validators and canonical output writers\\n- **Why it matters:** S1 is one of the strongest sectors conceptually and is the best early place to start real production implementation. Its outputs become the foundation for downstream work.\\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 1.2, 1.3, 1.4, and 2.2.\\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\\n  - `docs/branches/01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md`\\n  - `workspace_mirror/branches/01_pre_production/**`\\n  - new modules such as:\\n    - `runtime/s1/screenplay_validator.py`\\n    - `runtime/s1/polish_validator.py`\\n    - `runtime/s1/scene_bible_schema_validator.py`\\n    - `runtime/s1/checkpoint_writer.py`\\n- **Done criteria:**\\n  - S1 outputs can be validated deterministically\\n  - initial scene_bible artefact can be written in canonical form\\n  - S1 emits valid checkpoints and failure diagnostics\\n- **Priority:** P0\\n\\n## Task 3.2 — Unify and implement S2 audio generation, transcription, timestamp alignment, and bible updates\\n- **Why it matters:** S2 is strategically important because it introduces real timing. But the audit explicitly says S2 is split across competing versions, so Claude Code should fix the contract while implementing it.\\n- **Dependencies:** Tasks 0.1, 0.3, 1.2, and 2.3.\\n- **Likely files/modules to touch:**\\n  - `docs/branches/02_AUDIO.md`\\n  - `workspace_mirror/branches/02_audio/**`\\n  - new modules such as:\\n    - `runtime/s2/tts_generator.py`\\n    - `runtime/s2/audio_transcriber.py`\\n    - `runtime/s2/timestamp_aligner.py`\\n    - `runtime/s2/bible_updater.py`\\n    - `runtime/s2/alignment_confidence_checker.py`\\n- **Done criteria:**\\n  - there is one canonical S2 flow documented and implemented\\n  - TTS audio, alignment output, and timing artefacts are written predictably\\n  - scene_bible is updated with temporal data via the shared I/O layer\\n  - confidence/failure cases are surfaced for retry/escalation\\n- **Priority:** P0\\n\\n## Task 3.3 — Implement S4 asset ingestion, validation, dedupe, and indexing core\\n- **Why it matters:** S4 is mature enough to implement early and creates reusable assets that strengthen S5 and S6 instead of leaving them to operate on weak upstream data.\\n- **Dependencies\n...(truncated)..."}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":21634,"output":7096,"totalTokens":50234,"cacheRead":21504,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"total":0.165901}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774794470753,"responseId":"resp_043858592f200ba20169c936e880508191957f12b667789be2","__openclaw":{"id":"9d016e11","seq":12}},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Done — I created:\n\n- `reviews\\tobias_review_29mar\\26_claude_code_task_backlog.md`\n\nWhat it contains:\n- backlog grouped by implementation phase\n- each task includes:\n  - title\n  - why it matters\n  - dependencies\n  - likely files/modules to touch\n  - done criteria\n  - priority (P0/P1)\n- strong bias toward practical engineering bundles, not micro-tasks\n- implementation order aligned with the audit:\n  - contract freeze\n  - shared substrate\n  - PM + wrappers\n  - S1/S2/S4\n  - S3/S5/S6\n  - S7/S8\n  - S9/S10\n  - VO last\n\nRelevant note:\n- the repo appears to be mostly documentation + workspace mirror right now, with no established runtime code tree yet, so I framed likely implementation targets as new shared runtime modules (`runtime/` or `src/`) plus the existing docs/mirror areas that Claude Code will need to align while implementing.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_043858592f200ba20169c9376dfb44819184c4eb84b781e060\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":238,"output":218,"totalTokens":50504,"cacheRead":50048,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"total":0.016377}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774794603621,"responseId":"resp_043858592f200ba20169c9376d58748191aacbb455fb5e0fba","__openclaw":{"id":"c6408d50","seq":14}}]},{"key":"agent:main:subagent:dc24faab-3aae-482a-a304-961eabe592a2","kind":"other","channel":"webchat","spawnedBy":"agent:main:main","label":"session-battle-board","displayName":"webchat:g-agent-main-subagent-dc24faab-3aae-482a-a304-961eabe592a2","parentSessionKey":"agent:main:main","deliveryContext":{"channel":"webchat"},"updatedAt":1774794562922,"sessionId":"dc92ec7d-5e11-408b-b1b2-bb2094b4e858","model":"gpt-5.4","contextTokens":272000,"totalTokens":22844,"estimatedCostUsd":0.1424165,"status":"done","startedAt":1774794485741,"endedAt":1774794553596,"runtimeMs":62886,"abortedLastRun":false,"lastChannel":"webchat","transcriptPath":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\main\\sessions\\dc92ec7d-5e11-408b-b1b2-bb2094b4e858.jsonl","messages":[{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":""},{"type":"text","text":"Vou condensar os reviews num board operacional de 1 página, focado em ordem de sessão, bloqueios reais, decisões ao vivo e tickets prontos para Claude Code.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0720d1a20670abea0169c93707f204819184e9fe23e5cc7a4d\",\"phase\":\"commentary\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_kdxlG2z3JQ3AJDOVglM2Keqs|fc_0720d1a20670abea0169c93707ff08819182e4785aae33622e","name":"write","arguments":{"file":"C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\reviews\\tobias_review_29mar\\22_session_battle_board.md","content":"# Session Battle Board — 29 Mar 2026\n\n## Mission of the live session\n- **Goal:** sair da sessão com a base certa para implementação, não com falsa sensação de progresso.\n- **Rule:** primeiro fechar linguagem + contratos + ownership; só depois empurrar código pesado.\n- **North star:** reduzir drift documental e transformar o sistema em substrate implementável.\n\n## Recommended live order\n1. **Freeze canónico (15-25 min)**\n   - confirmar naming único: `s#_`, checkpoints, artefactos JSON, TSX, paths\n   - confirmar docs centrais prioritários: `04`, `09`, `12`\n   - confirmar quais mirrors estão a valer vs quais estão obsoletos\n2. **Fechar contratos core (25-40 min)**\n   - `scene_bible` I/O: read / lock / merge / write / version\n   - checkpoint contract\n   - structured error contract\n   - handoffs: S4→S5, S5→S6, S6→S7, S8→S9, S9→S10\n3. **Escolher lote P0 para Claude Code (20-30 min)**\n   - shared infra first\n   - PM core minimal\n   - S1 + S2 unblock\n4. **Definir o que NÃO entra agora (5-10 min)**\n   - VO pleno\n   - S9 pesado\n   - browser-heavy S6 sem contrato fechado\n5. **Encerrar com board de execução (5 min)**\n   - owners\n   - artefactos esperados\n   - critérios de done\n\n## Sector status\n\n### Ready to refine now\n- **PM / core infra**\n  - `read_pub`, `job_builder`, `job_validator`, `video_dir_initializer`\n- **S1**\n  - forte conceptualmente; falta validator + checkpoint discipline\n- **S4**\n  - suficientemente maduro para contrato inicial\n- **Shared validators / schema runtime**\n  - alto leverage transversal\n\n### Blocked until contracts are frozen\n- **S2**\n  - ainda em duas versões; unificar antes de implementar forte\n- **S5**\n  - bom desenho, mas precisa schemas/interfaces fechadas\n- **S6**\n  - depende de `prompt_builder`, browser contract, `portrait_manager`, output manifest\n- **S7**\n  - pronto só depois de builder input + TSX naming estarem canónicos\n- **S8**\n  - precisa fechar lettering ownership + output contract\n- **S10**\n  - conceptualmente simples, mas depende de output/idempotência/checkpoint final\n\n### Do later / do not force live\n- **VO pleno**\n  - não orquestrar incerteza cedo demais\n- **S9**\n  - maior nó de contradições; resolver depois de S7/S8 congelarem\n- **optimizações / telemetry / fallback refinado**\n  - baixo leverage agora\n\n## Top live decisions to make\n- Naming final: `s#_` vs qualquer legado restante\n- Docs fonte de verdade: quais ficheiros centrais mandam de facto\n- Política de mirror: o que actualizar, o que ignorar, o que marcar como stale\n- Contrato do `scene_bible`: ownership, locking, merge, partial update, versioning\n- Convenção única de checkpoints e paths\n- Forma canónica dos handoffs críticos entre setores\n- Estratégia temporária: adapter layer ou freeze-clean-first\n- Critério para considerar S2 “unificado” e S9 “desbloqueado”\n\n## Best items to hand Claude Code\n\n### Batch A — highest leverage first\n- criar/actualizar schemas JSON dos artefactos core por setor\n- implementar shared `scene_bible` I/O contract\n- implementar shared checkpoint helpers\n- implementar shared schema validation runtime\n- definir enums/structures para structured errors\n\n### Batch B — minimal productive substrate\n- PM: `read_pub`, `job_builder`, `job_validator`\n- VO-lite: `video_dir_initializer`, `checkpoint_resolver`, `sector_dispatcher` mínimo\n- wrappers: Sheets, TTS, WhisperX\n\n### Batch C — first implementable chain\n- S1 validators: `screenplay_validator`, `polish_validator`, `scene_bible_schema_validator`\n- S2 core: `tts_generator`, `audio_transcriber`, `timestamp_aligner`, `bible_updater`\n- S4 core: `asset_json_schema_validator`, `asset_deduplicator`, `asset_license_validator`\n\n## Top traps to avoid during the session\n- começar por S6 porque parece mais excitante\n- discutir arquitectura nova sem congelar contratos existentes\n- implementar VO cedo demais\n- aceitar docs centrais e mirror como se ambos fossem verdade ao mesmo tempo\n- codar sobre naming ambíguo (`b#_` / `s#_`, `scene_id` / `moment_id`, `duration_frames` / `duration_ms`)\n- entrar em S9 antes de congelar S7/S8\n- deixar `scene_bible` crescer sem governação forte\n- sair da sessão com “direcção” mas sem decisões canónicas escritas\n\n## Suggested meeting / workflow cadence\n- **0-10 min:** alinhar missão da sessão + definir o que precisa sair decidido\n- **10-35 min:** freeze de naming, docs fonte de verdade, mirrors, handoffs\n- **35-60 min:** fechar contracts core (`scene_bible`, checkpoints, errors)\n- **60-85 min:** transformar decisões em tickets claros para Claude Code\n- **85-100 min:** rever o que ficou fora, dependências e ordem exacta do próximo lote\n\n## Session close checklist\n- [ ] naming canónico decidido\n- [ ] docs centrais prioritários identificados para update\n- [ ] política de mirror decidida\n- [ ] `scene_bible` contract fechado\n- [ ] checkpoint contract fechado\n- [ ] batch P0 para Claude Code definido\n- [ ] explicitamente adiado: VO pleno + S9 pesado + S6 browser-heavy\n\n## Default recommendation if debate stalls\n- **Follow this order:**\n  - Freeze\n  - Shared infra\n  - PM core\n  - S1\n  - S2 unificado\n  - S4\n  - S3 hardening\n  - S5\n  - S6\n  - S7\n  - S8\n  - S9\n  - S10\n  - VO pleno\n"},"partialJson":"{\"file\":\"C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory\\\\reviews\\\\tobias_review_29mar\\\\22_session_battle_board.md\",\"content\":\"# Session Battle Board — 29 Mar 2026\\n\\n## Mission of the live session\\n- **Goal:** sair da sessão com a base certa para implementação, não com falsa sensação de progresso.\\n- **Rule:** primeiro fechar linguagem + contratos + ownership; só depois empurrar código pesado.\\n- **North star:** reduzir drift documental e transformar o sistema em substrate implementável.\\n\\n## Recommended live order\\n1. **Freeze canónico (15-25 min)**\\n   - confirmar naming único: `s#_`, checkpoints, artefactos JSON, TSX, paths\\n   - confirmar docs centrais prioritários: `04`, `09`, `12`\\n   - confirmar quais mirrors estão a valer vs quais estão obsoletos\\n2. **Fechar contratos core (25-40 min)**\\n   - `scene_bible` I/O: read / lock / merge / write / version\\n   - checkpoint contract\\n   - structured error contract\\n   - handoffs: S4→S5, S5→S6, S6→S7, S8→S9, S9→S10\\n3. **Escolher lote P0 para Claude Code (20-30 min)**\\n   - shared infra first\\n   - PM core minimal\\n   - S1 + S2 unblock\\n4. **Definir o que NÃO entra agora (5-10 min)**\\n   - VO pleno\\n   - S9 pesado\\n   - browser-heavy S6 sem contrato fechado\\n5. **Encerrar com board de execução (5 min)**\\n   - owners\\n   - artefactos esperados\\n   - critérios de done\\n\\n## Sector status\\n\\n### Ready to refine now\\n- **PM / core infra**\\n  - `read_pub`, `job_builder`, `job_validator`, `video_dir_initializer`\\n- **S1**\\n  - forte conceptualmente; falta validator + checkpoint discipline\\n- **S4**\\n  - suficientemente maduro para contrato inicial\\n- **Shared validators / schema runtime**\\n  - alto leverage transversal\\n\\n### Blocked until contracts are frozen\\n- **S2**\\n  - ainda em duas versões; unificar antes de implementar forte\\n- **S5**\\n  - bom desenho, mas precisa schemas/interfaces fechadas\\n- **S6**\\n  - depende de `prompt_builder`, browser contract, `portrait_manager`, output manifest\\n- **S7**\\n  - pronto só depois de builder input + TSX naming estarem canónicos\\n- **S8**\\n  - precisa fechar lettering ownership + output contract\\n- **S10**\\n  - conceptualmente simples, mas depende de output/idempotência/checkpoint final\\n\\n### Do later / do not force live\\n- **VO pleno**\\n  - não orquestrar incerteza cedo demais\\n- **S9**\\n  - maior nó de contradições; resolver depois de S7/S8 congelarem\\n- **optimizações / telemetry / fallback refinado**\\n  - baixo leverage agora\\n\\n## Top live decisions to make\\n- Naming final: `s#_` vs qualquer legado restante\\n- Docs fonte de verdade: quais ficheiros centrais mandam de facto\\n- Política de mirror: o que actualizar, o que ignorar, o que marcar como stale\\n- Contrato do `scene_bible`: ownership, locking, merge, partial update, versioning\\n- Convenção única de checkpoints e paths\\n- Forma canónica dos handoffs críticos entre setores\\n- Estratégia temporária: adapter layer ou freeze-clean-first\\n- Critério para considerar S2 “unificado” e S9 “desbloqueado”\\n\\n## Best items to hand Claude Code\\n\\n### Batch A — highest leverage first\\n- criar/actualizar schemas JSON dos artefactos core por setor\\n- implementar shared `scene_bible` I/O contract\\n- implementar shared checkpoint helpers\\n- implementar shared schema validation runtime\\n- definir enums/structures para structured errors\\n\\n### Batch B — minimal productive substrate\\n- PM: `read_pub`, `job_builder`, `job_validator`\\n- VO-lite: `video_dir_initializer`, `checkpoint_resolver`, `sector_dispatcher` mínimo\\n- wrappers: Sheets, TTS, WhisperX\\n\\n### Batch C — first implementable chain\\n- S1 validators: `screenplay_validator`, `polish_validator`, `scene_bible_schema_validator`\\n- S2 core: `tts_generator`, `audio_transcriber`, `timestamp_aligner`, `bible_updater`\\n- S4 core: `asset_json_schema_validator`, `asset_deduplicator`, `asset_license_validator`\\n\\n## Top traps to avoid during the session\\n- começar por S6 porque parece mais excitante\\n- discutir arquitectura nova sem congelar contratos existentes\\n- implementar VO cedo demais\\n- aceitar docs centrais e mirror como se ambos fossem verdade ao mesmo tempo\\n- codar sobre naming ambíguo (`b#_` / `s#_`, `scene_id` / `moment_id`, `duration_frames` / `duration_ms`)\\n- entrar em S9 antes de congelar S7/S8\\n- deixar `scene_bible` crescer sem governação forte\\n- sair da sessão com “direcção” mas sem decisões canónicas escritas\\n\\n## Suggested meeting / workflow cadence\\n- **0-10 min:** alinhar missão da sessão + definir o que precisa sair decidido\\n- **10-35 min:** freeze de naming, docs fonte de verdade, mirrors, handoffs\\n- **35-60 min:** fechar contracts core (`scene_bible`, checkpoints, errors)\\n- **60-85 min:** transformar decisões em tickets claros para Claude Code\\n- **85-100 min:** rever o que ficou fora, dependências e ordem exacta do próximo lote\\n\\n## Session close checklist\\n- [ ] naming canónico decidido\\n- [ ] docs centrais prioritários identificados para update\\n- [ ] política de mirror decidida\\n- [ ] `scene_bible` contract fechado\\n- [ ] checkpoint contract fechado\\n- [ ] batch P0 para Claude Code definido\\n- [ ] explicitamente adiado: VO pleno + S9 pesado + S6 browser-heavy\\n\\n## Default recommendation if debate stalls\\n- **Follow this order:**\\n  - Freeze\\n  - Shared infra\\n  - PM core\\n  - S1\\n  - S2 unificado\\n  - S4\\n  - S3 hardening\\n  - S5\\n  - S6\\n  - S7\\n  - S8\\n  - S9\\n  - S10\\n  - VO pleno\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":10768,"output":1531,"totalTokens":22795,"cacheRead":10496,"cacheWrite":0,"cost":{"total":0.052509}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774794498630,"responseId":"resp_0720d1a20670abea0169c937045bd08191ba9025931419b0a6","__openclaw":{"id":"c4c10c65","seq":8}},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Concluído.\n\nCriei o ficheiro:\n- `C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\reviews\\tobias_review_29mar\\22_session_battle_board.md`\n\nO board está comprimido e operacional, cobrindo:\n- ordem recomendada para a sessão ao vivo\n- status por setor: ready / blocked / do later\n- decisões principais a fechar live\n- batches prontos para entregar ao Claude Code\n- traps a evitar\n- cadence sugerida da reunião/workflow\n- checklist de fecho\n\nPonto central do board:\n- a sessão deve optimizar para **freeze de contratos + shared infra + lote P0 implementável**\n- e **evitar cair em VO pleno / S9 / S6 browser-heavy cedo demais**.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0720d1a20670abea0169c937380eac819181ebf262c7eff349\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":22844,"output":167,"totalTokens":230